> - **Topic:** Constructors

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition:**
> A **Constructor** in Object-Oriented Programming is a special member function (method) of a class that is **automatically invoked** at the time of object creation. Its primary purpose is to **initialize** the data members (instance variables) of the newly created object to meaningful, valid, and safe initial values.

### 1.1 Conceptual Analogy тАФ The "Hospital Admission Form"

Imagine you walk into a hospital for the first time.
1. The moment you arrive at the **Reception Desk (Class)**, you are not yet a "patient" тАФ you are just a visitor.
2. The receptionist hands you an **Admission Form (Constructor)** that you *must* fill out before any treatment begins.
3. The form **automatically pops up** the moment you register тАФ you don't call it manually.
4. The form sets your **Name, Age, Blood Group, Allergies (Instance Variables)** to specific, valid initial values.

In OOP terms:
- The **Class** is the blueprint of a Patient record.
- The **Object** is a specific patient.
- The **Constructor** is the admission form тАФ it runs automatically, exactly once, the moment a new `Patient` object is born in memory, guaranteeing the object is never left in a "wild" or uninitialized state.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Highlight:** Constructors have **no return type** (not even `void`) in Java, and they share the **exact same name** as the class. In C++, they share the class name but technically have no return type either.

### 1.2 Rules That Define a Constructor

| # | Rule | Reason |
|---|------|--------|
| 1 | Name must be **identical to the class name** | Compiler identifies it uniquely |
| 2 | **No return type** (not even `void`) | It is not a function returning a value; it builds the object |
| 3 | Invoked **automatically** when `new` is used (Java) / object is declared (C++) | Guarantees initialization |
| 4 | **Cannot be `abstract`, `static`, `final`, or `synchronized`** in Java | Conflicts with object creation semantics |
| 5 | Can be **overloaded** (multiple constructors) | Different ways to initialize an object |
| 6 | Can use **access modifiers** (`public`, `private`, `protected`) | Controls who can create objects |

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Types of Constructors (KTU High-Yield Topic)

### A. Default Constructor (No-Argument Constructor)
- A constructor that takes **zero parameters**.
- If the programmer writes **no constructor at all**, the compiler **automatically generates** a public no-arg constructor.
- If the programmer writes **any** constructor, the compiler **stops** providing the default one.

```java
class Student {
    int rollNo;
    String name;

    // Default Constructor (explicitly written)
    Student() {
        rollNo = 0;
        name = "Not Assigned";
    }
}
```

### B. Parameterized Constructor
- Accepts **arguments** to initialize fields with user-supplied values.
- Provides **flexibility** during object creation.

```java
class Student {
    int rollNo;
    String name;

    Student(int r, String n) {
        rollNo = r;
        name = n;
    }
}
```

### C. Copy Constructor
- Takes an **object of the same class** as a parameter and copies its values into the new object.
- **Built-in in C++**, but **must be manually written in Java** (Java uses `clone()` for deep copy logic).

```java
class Student {
    int rollNo;
    String name;

    Student(Student s) {
        rollNo = s.rollNo;
        name = s.name;
    }
}
```

### D. Private Constructor (Sentinel Pattern)
- Declared `private` to **prevent external object creation**.
- Used in **Singleton Design Pattern** and utility/helper classes containing only `static` methods.

### E. Constructor Overloading
- Defining **multiple constructors** within the same class with **different parameter lists** (number, type, or order of parameters).
- Resolved at **compile time** based on the arguments passed to `new`.

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet тАФ Constructor Behavior Rules

| Concept | Rule | Key Point for Exams |
|---------|------|---------------------|
| Default Constructor | Inserted by compiler **only if no constructor exists** | Writing one constructor removes auto-default |
| Parameterized | Enables custom initialization | Each parameter is a local variable inside constructor |
| Copy Constructor | Used in C++ for `MyClass obj2 = obj1;` | Java lacks it natively |
| Constructor Overloading | Differentiated by **signature** (parameter list) | Return type alone cannot overload |
| `this()` Call | Must be the **first statement** of constructor | Used for constructor chaining |
| Destructor | C++ only, name is `~ClassName` | Java uses Garbage Collector (no user destructor) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Utility:** Constructors enforce the **"invariants"** of a class тАФ the conditions that must always be true for an object to be valid (e.g., a `BankAccount` must never have a negative balance). They are the first line of defense for **robust software design**.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Demonstration: The `this` Keyword & Constructor Chaining

Below is a **fully fleshed-out Java program** with line-by-line execution logic. This is a classic **14-mark KTU Part B** question pattern.

```java
class Box {
    double width, height, depth;

    // 1я╕ПтГг Parameterized constructor
    Box(double w, double h, double d) {
        width  = w;   // 'this' is implicit; 'w' is local parameter
        height = h;
        depth  = d;
        System.out.println("Parameterized constructor called.");
    }

    // 2я╕ПтГг Cube constructor тАФ chains to main constructor
    Box(double side) {
        this(side, side, side);   // calls the 3-arg constructor
        System.out.println("Cube constructor called.");
    }

    // 3я╕ПтГг No-arg constructor тАФ creates unit cube
    Box() {
        this(1.0);               // calls the 1-arg constructor
        System.out.println("Default constructor called.");
    }

    double volume() {
        return width * height * depth;
    }
}
```

### 3.2 Step-by-Step Execution Trace

Suppose a KTU exam asks: *What is the output of the following?*
```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Box b1 = new Box(2.0, 3.0, 4.0);
    Box b2 = new Box(5.0);
    Box b3 = new Box();
    System.out.println("V1 = " + b1.volume());
    System.out.println("V2 = " + b2.volume());
    System.out.println("V3 = " + b3.volume());
}
```

| Step | Action | Constructor Entered | Print Statement Executed | `width ├Ч height ├Ч depth` |
|------|--------|--------------------|--------------------------|--------------------------|
| 1 | `new Box(2.0, 3.0, 4.0)` | 3-arg directly | "Parameterized constructor called." | 2 ├Ч 3 ├Ч 4 = **24.0** |
| 2 | `new Box(5.0)` | 1-arg тЖТ `this(5,5,5)` тЖТ 3-arg | "Parameterized..." then "Cube..." | 5 ├Ч 5 ├Ч 5 = **125.0** |
| 3 | `new Box()` | no-arg тЖТ `this(1.0)` тЖТ 1-arg тЖТ 3-arg | "Parameterized...", "Cube...", "Default..." | 1 ├Ч 1 ├Ч 1 = **1.0** |

### 3.3 Output (Exact Order)

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Parameterized constructor called.} \\
\text{Parameterized constructor called.} \\
\text{Cube constructor called.} \\
\text{Parameterized constructor called.} \\
\text{Cube constructor called.} \\
\text{Default constructor called.} \\
V1 = 24.0 \\
V2 = 125.0 \\
V3 = 1.0
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Derivation Logic:** When constructor chaining uses `this(...)`, control jumps to the called constructor first, completes it fully, and **then** resumes the remaining statements of the calling constructor. This is **Stack-Based Execution** (LIFO unwind).

## 3.4 Constructor vs Method тАФ Comparative Matrix

| Property | Constructor | Method |
|----------|-------------|--------|
| Name | Same as class | Any valid identifier |
| Return type | None (not even void) | Required (or void) |
| Invocation | Automatic via `new` | Manual via object reference |
| Inheritance | Not inherited | Inherited |
| Overloading | Yes | Yes |
| `final`/`static` allowed? | No | Yes |
| Purpose | Initialize object | Perform action on object |

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
