# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## ЁЯУШ Part A тАФ Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Q1. [KTU University Exam тАФ Dec 2023]
**Differentiate between a constructor and a method in Java. Can a constructor be declared `final` or `static`? Justify.**

**Model Answer:**
A **constructor** is a special member function used to initialize an object, has the **same name as the class**, and **no return type**. It is **invoked automatically** when an object is created using `new`.

A **method** is a general member function that performs a specific action, has **any valid name**, **must specify a return type** (or `void`), and is **invoked explicitly** using an object reference.

A constructor **cannot** be declared `final` (because constructors are never inherited, so `final` is meaningless) and **cannot** be `static` (because static members belong to the class, but constructors must operate on instance data of a specific object).

*(3 marks тАФ concise definition, clear distinction, valid justification)*

### Q2. [KTU University Exam тАФ June 2024]
**What is a copy constructor? Write a Java program to demonstrate it.**

**Model Answer:**
A **copy constructor** is a constructor that takes an object of the **same class** as a parameter and initializes a new object with the values of the existing object.

```java
class Point {
    int x, y;

    Point(int a, int b) { x = a; y = b; }

    Point(Point p) {      // Copy constructor
        x = p.x;
        y = p.y;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("x = " + x + ", y = " + y);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Point p1 = new Point(10, 20);
        Point p2 = new Point(p1);
        p2.display();
    }
}
```

*(3 marks тАФ definition 1 mark, code 2 marks)*

---

## ЁЯУЧ Part B тАФ Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each тАФ Internal Choice)

### тЭУ Question A (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam тАФ Dec 2023]

**(a)** Explain the concept of **constructor overloading** in Java with a suitable example. *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Write a Java program to demonstrate the use of the **`this` keyword** to refer to:
- (i) current instance variables
- (ii) current object
- (iii) constructor chaining using `this()`

Provide the complete program and explain its output. *(7 marks)*

---

### тЬЕ Model Solution for Question A

#### (a) Constructor Overloading тАФ Explanation (7 marks)

**Definition:** Constructor overloading is the technique of defining **multiple constructors** within the same class, each having a **different parameter list** (varying in number, type, or order of parameters). It allows objects to be initialized in **different ways** depending on the data available at the time of creation.

**Why is it useful?**
- It provides **flexibility** тАФ sometimes we have all data, sometimes only partial.
- It improves **readability** and supports **polymorphism** at object creation time.
- The compiler resolves which constructor to call at **compile time** based on the arguments passed (a form of **static/compile-time polymorphism**).

**Example Program:**
```java
class Employee {
    String name;
    int id;
    double salary;

    // Constructor 1: No-arg
    Employee() {
        name = "Unknown";
        id = 0;
        salary = 0.0;
    }

    // Constructor 2: Two parameters
    Employee(String n, int i) {
        name = n;
        id = i;
        salary = 25000.0;  // default salary
    }

    // Constructor 3: Three parameters
    Employee(String n, int i, double s) {
        name = n;
        id = i;
        salary = s;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(id + " | " + name + " | тВ╣" + salary);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e1 = new Employee();
        Employee e2 = new Employee("Arun", 101);
        Employee e3 = new Employee("Meera", 102, 75000.0);

        e1.display();
        e2.display();
        e3.display();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
0 | Unknown | тВ╣0.0
101 | Arun | тВ╣25000.0
102 | Meera | тВ╣75000.0
```

**Resolution:** The compiler matches the arguments in `new Employee(...)` with the parameter signatures of the three constructors, choosing the best match. This is resolved at **compile time** тАФ hence, constructor overloading is a form of **static polymorphism**.

---

#### (b) `this` Keyword тАФ Demonstration (7 marks)

The `this` keyword in Java is a **reference variable** that refers to the **current object** тАФ the object whose method or constructor is being executed.

**Three uses demonstrated:**

```java
class Student {
    int rollNo;
    String name;
    String college;

    // Use (iii): Constructor chaining using this()
    Student() {
        this(0, "Not Assigned", "KTU");   // calls 3-arg constructor
    }

    Student(int rollNo, String name) {
        this.rollNo = rollNo;              // (i) refers to current instance var
        this.name = name;
        this.college = "KTU";
    }

    Student(int rollNo, String name, String college) {
        this.rollNo = rollNo;              // (i)
        this.name = name;                  // (i)
        this.college = college;
    }

    void print(Student obj) {
        System.out.println("Roll: " + obj.rollNo);
    }

    void show() {
        print(this);                       // (ii) 'this' refers to current object
        System.out.println("College: " + college);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student();
        Student s2 = new Student(7, "Anu");
        Student s3 = new Student(8, "Rahul", "CET");

        s1.show();
        s2.show();
        s3.show();
    }
}
```

**Explanation of three uses:**
1. **`this.rollNo = rollNo;`** тАФ Disambiguates between the **instance variable** and the **local parameter** when both share the same name.
2. **`print(this);`** тАФ Passes the **current object** as an argument to another method.
3. **`this(0, "Not Assigned", "KTU");`** тАФ Invokes another constructor in the same class (constructor chaining). **Must be the first statement** of the constructor.

---

### тЭУ Question B (14 Marks) тАФ ALTERNATIVE CHOICE [KTU University Exam тАФ June 2024]

**(a)** Explain the **default constructor** and **parameterized constructor** with examples. What happens if a class defines only a parameterized constructor and you try to create an object with no arguments? *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Write a Java program to define a class `Rectangle` with length and breadth. Demonstrate:
- A **default constructor** that sets dimensions to 1.
- A **parameterized constructor** that accepts dimensions.
- A **copy constructor** that creates a new rectangle from an existing one.
- A method `area()` that returns the area.

*(7 marks)*

---

### тЬЕ Model Solution for Question B

#### (a) Default vs Parameterized Constructor (7 marks)

**Default Constructor:** A constructor that accepts **no arguments** is called a *default constructor*. It initializes all instance variables to their **default values** (numeric тЖТ 0, boolean тЖТ false, object refs тЖТ null). If the programmer writes **no constructor at all**, the compiler **automatically provides a public default constructor**.

```java
class Demo {
    int x;
    Demo() {                 // Explicit default constructor
        x = 100;
    }
}
```

**Parameterized Constructor:** A constructor that accepts **one or more parameters** is called a *parameterized constructor*. It allows the caller to pass initial values at the time of object creation.

```java
class Demo {
    int x;
    Demo(int val) {          // Parameterized
        x = val;
    }
}
```

**Critical Concept тАФ If only a parameterized constructor exists:**
```java
class Demo {
    int x;
    Demo(int val) { x = val; }   // Only parameterized
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    Demo d = new Demo();   // тЭМ COMPILE-TIME ERROR
}
```
The compiler will throw: **"constructor Demo in class Demo cannot be applied to given types; required: int, found: no arguments"**.

**Why?** The compiler **only** auto-generates a default constructor if the programmer has **not written any constructor at all**. The moment you write a parameterized constructor, the auto-default is **removed**. The programmer must then **explicitly write** a no-arg constructor if needed.

---

#### (b) Rectangle Class тАФ Full Program (7 marks)

```java
class Rectangle {
    double length, breadth;

    // Default constructor
    Rectangle() {
        length = 1.0;
        breadth = 1.0;
        System.out.println("Default constructor called.");
    }

    // Parameterized constructor
    Rectangle(double l, double b) {
        length = l;
        breadth = b;
        System.out.println("Parameterized constructor called.");
    }

    // Copy constructor
    Rectangle(Rectangle r) {
        length = r.length;
        breadth = r.breadth;
        System.out.println("Copy constructor called.");
    }

    double area() {
        return length * breadth;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Rectangle r1 = new Rectangle();
        Rectangle r2 = new Rectangle(5.0, 3.0);
        Rectangle r3 = new Rectangle(r2);

        System.out.println("Area r1: " + r1.area());
        System.out.println("Area r2: " + r2.area());
        System.out.println("Area r3: " + r3.area());
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Default constructor called.
Parameterized constructor called.
Copy constructor called.
Area r1: 1.0
Area r2: 15.0
Area r3: 15.0
```

> [!WARNING]
> **ЁЯЪи KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning тАФ Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting the default constructor after adding a parameterized one** тАФ students often write `new ClassName()` expecting it to work, leading to compile-time errors. **Loss: 2 marks.**
> 2. **Using a return type with a constructor** (e.g., `void Rectangle()`) тАФ this turns it into a regular method, not a constructor. **Loss: 2 marks.**
> 3. **Placing `this()` call NOT as the first statement** тАФ the compiler will reject it. **Loss: 1 mark.**
> 4. **Confusing `this` (current object) with `this()` (constructor call)** тАФ they look similar but are syntactically different. **Loss: 1 mark.**
> 5. **In copy constructors, forgetting to handle deep copy of object references** тАФ for fields like `String[]`, a shallow copy can cause aliasing bugs. (Mentioned in 14-mark answers, partial credit can still be awarded.)

---

## ЁЯФБ Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Yield Rapid Revision Checklist тАФ Constructors**

- тнР **Constructor = Class Name + No Return Type** тАФ the two golden identifiers.
- тнР **Auto-Default Constructor Rule:** provided **only** if the class has **zero** written constructors.
- тнР **Constructor Overloading** = multiple constructors, different parameter lists, compile-time polymorphism.
- тнР **Copy Constructor** = takes an object of the same class; built-in in C++, manual in Java.
- тнР **`this` Keyword** has **three** uses: instance-variable disambiguation, passing current object, and constructor chaining.
- тнР **`this()` call** must be the **first statement** in a constructor body.
- тнР **Constructors are NOT inherited** in Java (they belong to their own class only).
- тнР **Constructors cannot be** `abstract`, `static`, `final`, or `synchronized` in Java.
- тнР **Private constructors** are used to implement the **Singleton Design Pattern**.
- тнР **Destructors:** C++ has `~ClassName()`; Java has **Garbage Collection** (`finalize()` was deprecated in Java 9).
- тнР **Order of execution during object creation:** Static block тЖТ Instance initializer block тЖТ Constructor body.
- тнР **Memory:** Constructor allocates the object on the **heap**; the reference variable sits on the **stack**.
<!-- SECTION_5_END -->

> **APJ ABDUL KALAM TECHNOLOGICAL UNIVERSITY (KTU) | 2024 SCHEME**
> - **Course:** PBCST304 - OBJECT ORIENTED PROGRAMMING
> - **Module:** Module 2
> - **Topic:** Returning Objects

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# ЁЯУШ SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

In Object Oriented Programming (OOP), **Returning Objects** refers to the mechanism by which a method/function transfers the *reference* (or pointer) of an object тАФ instead of a primitive value тАФ back to the calling context. The method's declared return type is a *class type* (a user-defined data type), and the statement `return obj;` causes the runtime system to hand over the memory address of the object to the caller.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition (Module 2):** "A method in Java can return any type of data, including class types. That is, a method can return a reference to an object of any class type." тАФ *Herbert Schildt / KTU prescribed text, Object Oriented Programming through Java.*

**Key vocabulary used in KTU valuation:**
- **Caller** тАФ the code segment that invokes the method.
- **Return type (class type)** тАФ the data type declared in the method signature.
- **Reference variable** тАФ a variable that holds the memory address of an object on the heap.
- **Garbage Collector (GC)** тАФ the JVM component that reclaims heap memory for unreferenced objects.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy ЁЯН▒ тАФ The Parcel Counter

Imagine you walk into a courier office (the **method**) carrying a registered parcel. The clerk does some processing and instead of giving you a *photocopy* of the parcel (value), the clerk hands you the **original tracking slip** тАФ a piece of paper that *points to* the parcel still stored in the warehouse (heap memory).

- The **parcel** = the object stored in heap memory.
- The **tracking slip** = the reference variable.
- The **counter clerk** = the method returning the object.
- The **warehouse** = the JVM heap.
- The **delivery person (later)** = Garbage Collector, who removes the parcel if the slip is lost.

You do not receive a *duplicate* parcel тАФ you receive *access* to the same parcel. Any change you make is visible to everyone holding a slip to that parcel. This is the essence of **returning objects by reference**.

> [!NOTE]
> In Java, **everything is passed by value**, but for objects the "value passed/copied" is the *reference value* (address), not the object itself. This is the most common source of confusion in KTU viva-voce questions.

---

## 1.3 Why Returning Objects Matters in KTU Examinations

- Forms the **foundation for Factory Methods**, **Builder Pattern**, and **Singleton Design**.
- It is the **backbone of chaining methods** (e.g., `StringBuilder.append(...).append(...)`).
- Critical for understanding **immutable vs. mutable** object returns (e.g., `String` vs. `StringBuilder`).
- Direct **2-mark and 7-mark** frequency topic in KTU ESE papers.

> [!TIP]
> Examiners **love** asking: *"Explain how objects are returned from methods with an example."* тАФ It has appeared in KTU 2019, 2021, 2022, and 2023 ESE papers.

---

## 1.4 Two Conflicting Syntax Conventions тАФ *Java vs C++*

| Aspect | Java | C++ |
|---|---|---|
| Return type declaration | `public MyClass getObj()` | `MyClass getObj()` |
| What is returned? | A *copy of the reference* | A copy of the object, pointer, or reference |
| Memory managed by | JVM / Garbage Collector | Programmer (new/delete) |
| Dangling references | Not possible (GC protected) | Possible (manual deletion risk) |

Since **PBCST304 (OOP through Java)** is the KTU course code, **all examples below use Java**, and this is the language KTU expects in answers.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# ЁЯУШ SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Notes

## 2.1 Operational Breakdown тАФ How Object Return Works

A method returning an object operates in **four structured phases**:

1. **Declaration Phase** тАФ The method signature declares a *class type* as its return type.
   ```java
   access_modifier ClassName methodName(parameters) { ... }
   ```

2. **Object Construction Phase** тАФ Inside the method body, an object is instantiated (using `new`) or obtained (from parameters/other methods).

3. **Return Statement Phase** тАФ The statement `return objectReference;` transfers the *reference value* to the caller's receiving variable.

4. **Reception Phase** тАФ The caller captures the returned reference in a variable of the same class type. This variable now points to the **same object** that the method constructed.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Crucial KTU Point:** When a method finishes execution, its *local* variables are destroyed from the **stack**. However, if a local object reference was returned, the **object on the heap survives** because the caller now holds a reference to it. The stack frame dies; the heap object lives on.

---

## 2.2 Why Return an Object? тАФ Engineering Utility

- **Encapsulation of Construction Logic** тАФ The caller doesn't need to know *how* the object is built; the method hides complexity (this is the **Factory Method** pattern).
- **Chaining** тАФ Enables fluent interfaces (`objA.set(x).set(y).build()`).
- **Returning Modified Copies** тАФ Used in **immutable class design** (e.g., `LocalDate.plusDays()` returns a new `LocalDate`).
- **Returning Aggregates** тАФ A method can return an array of objects, a `List<>`, or a `Map<>` тАФ all are objects.
- **Returning `this`** тАФ Enables method chaining in the same instance.

---

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Reference Table (Cheat Sheet)

> [!NOTE]
> The following table summarizes **every critical rule** examiners expect students to memorize. Memorize this verbatim for the 14-mark question.

| # | Rule / Concept | Engineering Implication |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Methods can return *any* class type, including user-defined classes. | Foundation of Factory Pattern. |
| 2 | `return` statement copies the *reference* (not the object). | Two variables can point to the same object. |
| 3 | The returned object survives method exit (heap retention). | Enables asynchronous/builder use-cases. |
| 4 | Local objects of a method that are **not returned** are eligible for GC after method exit. | Memory efficiency. |
| 5 | If the return type is an **interface**, the method can return any class implementing it (polymorphic return). | Loose coupling, Strategy Pattern. |
| 6 | Methods can return arrays (arrays are objects in Java). | Used in `String[] split()`. |
| 7 | Returning `this` returns the *current* object reference. | Enables method chaining/fluent API. |
| 8 | Returning a `null` reference is legal for object return types. | Caller must guard against `NullPointerException`. |
| 9 | The compiler enforces *type compatibility* between the return statement and the declared return type. | Compile-time safety. |
| 10 | A method returning `Object` (the cosmic superclass) can return *any* Java object. | Used in `ArrayList.toArray()`. |

