## 2.6 Common Pitfalls Students Must Avoid

> [!WARNING]
> **Pitfall 1 тАФ Confusing *return by value of reference* with *return by reference (C++ feature)*.**  
> Java **does not** support C++-style true pass-by-reference. Always state: *"Java passes and returns a *copy* of the reference."*

> [!WARNING]
> **Pitfall 2 тАФ Forgetting that local primitives are destroyed but local object references transferred via `return` are NOT.**  
> Examiners test this with the question: *"Will the object created inside a method exist after the method returns? Justify."*

> [!WARNING]
> **Pitfall 3 тАФ Returning a reference to a local-only object (illegal in C++ with stack-allocated objects, but legal in Java because all objects live on the heap).**  
> In Java, you *can* safely return a locally created object because `new` allocates on the heap, not the stack.
