## 3.2 Problem 2 тАФ Returning `this` for Method Chaining (Builder Style)

**Problem Statement:**  
Design a class `Student` with fields `name`, `age`, and `grade`. Each setter should return the *current* object using `return this;` so calls can be chained. Test in `main`.

### Step-by-Step Solution

**Step 1 тАФ Class Definition**

```java
class Student {
    private String name;
    private int age;
    private char grade;

    public Student setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
        return this;   // <-- returns current object reference
    }

    public Student setAge(int age) {
        this.age = age;
        return this;
    }

    public Student setGrade(char grade) {
        this.grade = grade;
        return this;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age + ", Grade: " + grade);
    }
}
```

**Step 2 тАФ Driver**

```java
public class StudentDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student()
                        .setName("Ananya")
                        .setAge(20)
                        .setGrade('A');
        s.show();
    }
}
```

**Step 3 тАФ Output**

```
Name: Ananya, Age: 20, Grade: A
```

### Analytical Reasoning (Why it works)

$$\text{Each setter returns } \textit{this} \implies \text{next method is invoked on the same object}$$

$$\text{Chain } = \underbrace{\text{new Student()}}_{\text{Object @0xC1}}.\underbrace{\text{setName("Ananya")}}_{\text{returns @0xC1}}.\underbrace{\text{setAge(20)}}_{\text{returns @0xC1}}.\underbrace{\text{setGrade('A')}}_{\text{returns @0xC1}}$$

Therefore, **all four calls operate on the *same* heap object** at address `0xC1`.

