## 3.5 Problem 5 тАФ Polymorphic / Interface Return (Advanced)

**Problem Statement:**  
Define interface `Shape` with method `area()`. Create `Circle` and `Square` implementing it. A factory class `ShapeFactory` has a static method `getShape(String type)` that returns a `Shape` тАФ this is a polymorphic return.

### Step-by-Step Solution

```java
interface Shape {
    double area();
}

class Circle implements Shape {
    double r;
    public Circle(double r) { this.r = r; }
    public double area() { return Math.PI * r * r; }
}

class Square implements Shape {
    double s;
    public Square(double s) { this.s = s; }
    public double area() { return s * s; }
}

class ShapeFactory {
    public static Shape getShape(String type) {   // <-- interface return type
        if (type.equalsIgnoreCase("circle")) return new Circle(5);
        if (type.equalsIgnoreCase("square")) return new Square(4);
        return null;
    }
}

public class FactoryDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Shape s = ShapeFactory.getShape("circle");
        System.out.println("Area = " + s.area());
    }
}
```

### Why This Matters for KTU

The **declared return type** is `Shape` (an interface), but the **actual returned object** is `Circle` or `Square` (concrete classes). This is **polymorphism applied to return types** and is a guaranteed 14-mark or viva question on *loose coupling* and *factory pattern*.

