### тЬЕ Question A тАФ 14 Marks `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023 Model Paper]`

**(a)** Explain the concept of *returning objects* from methods in Java. What is the role of the `return` statement when the return type is a class? **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program with a class `Time` having members `hours` and `minutes`. Include a method `addTime(Time t1, Time t2)` that returns a new `Time` object representing the sum. Demonstrate the use of this method in `main`. **(7 marks)**

#### ЁЯУЭ Model Solution тАФ Part (a)

**Definition:** Returning an object from a method means transferring the *reference* of an object to the caller via the `return` statement. The method must declare a *class type* as its return type in its signature.

**Role of `return` statement:**
1. It specifies *which* object's reference is being handed back.
2. The compiler verifies that the type of the expression in `return` is *compatible* with the declared return type.
3. The reference value is **copied** into the caller's receiving variable.
4. The original method's local stack frame is destroyed, but the heap-allocated object **survives** because the caller now references it.

**Key snippet:**

```java
class Demo {
    Student build() {           // class type as return
        Student s = new Student();
        return s;               // returns reference to heap object
    }
}
```

**Conceptual memory model:**

```
STACK (caller)        HEAP
s1 --------+--------> Student @0xAA
                      {name, marks, ...}
```

The caller now has full read/write access to the same object constructed inside the method.

**Conclusion:** Returning objects is the cornerstone of OOP, enabling Factory patterns, Builder patterns, polymorphism, and fluent interfaces. **(7 marks)**

---

#### ЁЯУЭ Model Solution тАФ Part (b)

```java
class Time {
    int hours, minutes;

    public Time() { hours = 0; minutes = 0; }

    public Time(int h, int m) {
        hours = h;
        minutes = m;
    }

    // Static method that returns a Time object
    public static Time addTime(Time t1, Time t2) {
        Time sum = new Time();
        sum.minutes = t1.minutes + t2.minutes;
        sum.hours   = t1.hours   + t2.hours + (sum.minutes / 60);
        sum.minutes = sum.minutes % 60;
        return sum;     // <-- returns a Time object
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println(hours + "h " + minutes + "m");
    }
}

public class TimeDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Time t1 = new Time(2, 45);
        Time t2 = new Time(1, 30);
        Time total = Time.addTime(t1, t2);   // receives returned object
        System.out.print("Total time: ");
        total.display();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Total time: 4h 15m
```

**Explanation trace:**

$$
t_1 = 2 \text{h } 45 \text{m}, \quad t_2 = 1 \text{h } 30 \text{m}
$$

$$
\text{minutes}_{\text{raw}} = 45 + 30 = 75
$$

$$
\text{hours}_{\text{carry}} = \lfloor 75 / 60 \rfloor = 1, \quad \text{minutes}_{\text{final}} = 75 \bmod 60 = 15
$$

$$
\text{hours}_{\text{total}} = 2 + 1 + 1 = 4
$$

$$
\text{result} = 4 \text{h } 15 \text{m} \quad \blacksquare
$$

The static method `addTime` encapsulates the addition logic and returns a brand-new `Time` object built on the heap. **(7 marks)**

