### тЬЕ Question B тАФ 14 Marks (Alternative Choice) `[KTU University Exam - May 2024 Model Paper]`

**(a)** Discuss with examples the various ways of returning objects in Java: (i) returning a constructed object, (ii) returning `this`, (iii) returning an interface type, and (iv) returning an array of objects. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java program where a class `BankAccount` has fields `accountNo` and `balance`. Provide a method `transfer(BankAccount from, BankAccount to, double amt)` that debits `from`, credits `to`, and returns a `Transaction` object containing the details of the transfer. Demonstrate in `main`. **(7 marks)**

#### ЁЯУЭ Model Solution тАФ Part (a)

**(i) Returning a constructed object:**

```java
class Factory {
    public static Student createStudent() {
        return new Student("Default", 0);  // returns new object
    }
}
```

**(ii) Returning `this` (self-reference):**

```java
class Counter {
    int n = 0;
    Counter increment() { n++; return this; }   // returns current object
}
```

**(iii) Returning an interface type (polymorphic return):**

```java
interface Vehicle { void drive(); }
class Car implements Vehicle {
    public void drive() { System.out.println("Driving Car"); }
}
class Garage {
    public static Vehicle getVehicle() { return new Car(); }   // interface return
}
```

**(iv) Returning an array of objects:**

```java
class Library {
    public static Book[] getAllBooks() {
        return new Book[] { new Book("A"), new Book("B") };
    }
}
```

**Key conceptual points:**
- All four mechanisms rely on the *copying of the reference value* during return.
- (ii) enables fluent APIs.
- (iii) decouples the caller from concrete classes.
- (iv) is widely used in collections and data-retrieval methods. **(7 marks)**

---

#### ЁЯУЭ Model Solution тАФ Part (b)

```java
class Transaction {
    String fromAcc, toAcc;
    double amount;
    boolean success;

    public Transaction(String f, String t, double a, boolean s) {
        fromAcc = f; toAcc = t; amount = a; success = s;
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println("From: " + fromAcc + " | To: " + toAcc +
                           " | Amount: " + amount + " | Status: " +
                           (success ? "SUCCESS" : "FAILED"));
    }
}

class BankAccount {
    String accountNo;
    double balance;

    public BankAccount(String acc, double bal) {
        this.accountNo = acc;
        this.balance = bal;
    }

    public static Transaction transfer(BankAccount from, BankAccount to, double amt) {
        Transaction txn;
        if (from.balance >= amt) {
            from.balance -= amt;
            to.balance   += amt;
            txn = new Transaction(from.accountNo, to.accountNo, amt, true);
        } else {
            txn = new Transaction(from.accountNo, to.accountNo, amt, false);
        }
        return txn;     // <-- returns a Transaction object
    }
}

public class BankDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount a1 = new BankAccount("ACC001", 5000);
        BankAccount a2 = new BankAccount("ACC002", 2000);
        Transaction t = BankAccount.transfer(a1, a2, 1500);
        t.display();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
From: ACC001 | To: ACC002 | Amount: 1500.0 | Status: SUCCESS
```

**Conceptual demonstration:**  
The static `transfer` method **returns a Transaction object** that records the outcome of the transfer. This object is created inside the method, returned to the caller, and persists on the heap for further use (e.g., logging or audit). **(7 marks)**

