## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The `super` Keyword тАФ The Three Faces

The `super` keyword in Java is a **reference variable** that refers to the **immediate parent class object**. It has three distinct uses:

1. **`super.memberVariable`** тАФ Accesses the parent's instance variable when the sub class has shadowed it.
2. **`super.memberMethod()`** тАФ Invokes the parent's method (commonly used in method overriding to extend, not replace, behavior).
3. **`super(arguments)`** тАФ Explicitly invokes a parent class constructor from a sub class constructor.

### 2.2 Operational Logic тАФ Why and How

**Step 1 тАФ Class Declaration**
A sub class is declared using `extends`. The compiler links the sub class to its super class at **compile time**, building the inheritance hierarchy in the class metadata.

**Step 2 тАФ Object Instantiation**
When `new SubClass()` is executed, the **JVM allocates memory for BOTH the sub class object AND the super class portion** within the same contiguous object. The super class fields are embedded inside the sub class object.

**Step 3 тАФ Constructor Chaining (The Critical Step)**
The first executable statement in any constructor is either:
- An explicit call to `super(...)`, OR
- An explicit call to `this(...)`, OR
- A **compiler-inserted implicit** call to `super()` (no-argument parent constructor).

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Critical Rule:** If the parent class does **NOT** define a **no-argument constructor** and the sub class constructor does not explicitly call `super(args)`, the program **fails to compile**. This is one of the most common KTU viva questions and a frequent source of compilation errors in lab exams.

**Step 4 тАФ Member Access Resolution**
When a method is invoked on a sub class object, the JVM follows the **method resolution algorithm**:
1. Search the sub class for the method.
2. If not found, search the parent class.
3. Continue up the inheritance chain until `java.lang.Object`.
4. If still not found тЖТ `NoSuchMethodError` (at runtime) or compile error.

### 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Syntax / Rule | Visibility |
|---|---|---|
| Single Inheritance | `class B extends A` | Public / Protected / Package-private members inherited |
| Multilevel Inheritance | `C extends B extends A` | Transitive inheritance chain |
| Hierarchical Inheritance | `B, C, D all extend A` | One parent, many children |
| `super.variable` | Access hidden parent variable | Requires non-private access |
| `super.method()` | Invoke overridden parent method | Useful for code reuse + extension |
| `super()` | Call parent no-arg constructor | Must be **first line** of constructor |
| `super(args)` | Call parent parameterized constructor | Must be **first line** of constructor |
| Implicit `super()` | Compiler inserts if no explicit call | Fails if parent lacks no-arg constructor |
| Constructor inheritance | **Not inherited** | Must be redefined or chained |
| `final` class as super | **Not allowed** | `final` prevents inheritance |
| Diamond problem | **Avoided in Java** | No multiple class inheritance via `extends` |

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **GUI Frameworks:** JavaFX and Swing use deep super class chains (`Control` тЖТ `Labeled` тЖТ `Button`).
- **JDBC API:** `DriverManager` and `Connection` interfaces rely on inheritance for polymorphic driver registration.
- **Enterprise Java (Spring, Hibernate):** Entity classes inherit from base classes to gain ID, timestamp, and audit fields automatically.
- **Game Development:** A `GameObject` super class is extended by `Player`, `Enemy`, `Projectile`, `Pickup` тАФ providing a unified update/render loop.

