## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Analytical Example 1: `super.variable` to Resolve Shadowing

Consider the following Java program demonstrating variable shadowing and the use of `super.variable`:

```java
class Person {
    String name = "Parent Name";
}

class Student extends Person {
    String name = "Child Name";

    void printNames() {
        System.out.println("Child name : " + name);
        System.out.println("Parent name: " + super.name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
        s.printNames();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Child name : Child Name
Parent name: Parent Name
```

**Step-by-step Logic:**

1. The compiler sees two `name` fields тАФ one in `Person`, one in `Student`.
2. The `Student.name` **shadows** (hides) the `Person.name` for all references within `Student` methods.
3. The bare identifier `name` inside `printNames()` resolves to the **closest scope**, which is `Student.name`.
4. The prefix `super.` explicitly disambiguates and forces the compiler to resolve `name` in the **parent class scope**, yielding `"Parent Name"`.

### 3.2 Analytical Example 2: `super()` Constructor Chaining

```java
class Animal {
    Animal() {
        System.out.println("Animal constructor called");
    }
    Animal(String type) {
        System.out.println("Animal(String) constructor: " + type);
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    Dog() {
        super("Mammal");   // explicit call to parameterized parent constructor
        System.out.println("Dog constructor called");
    }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Animal(String) constructor: Mammal
Dog constructor called
```

**Step-by-step Logic:**

1. `main()` invokes `new Dog()`.
2. The `Dog()` constructor's **first statement** is `super("Mammal")`.
3. Control transfers to `Animal(String type)`, which prints the first line.
4. After `Animal(String)` finishes, control returns to `Dog()`, which prints the second line.

### 3.3 Analytical Example 3: `super.method()` in Method Overriding

```java
class Shape {
    void draw() {
        System.out.println("Drawing a generic shape");
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    @Override
    void draw() {
        super.draw();   // calls parent implementation
        System.out.println("Drawing a circle");
    }
}

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Circle c = new Circle();
        c.draw();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Drawing a generic shape
Drawing a circle
```

**Step-by-step Logic:**

1. The `Circle` class **overrides** `draw()` from `Shape`.
2. Without `super.draw()`, the parent's behavior would be completely lost.
3. `super.draw()` invokes the parent version, preserving and extending the original logic.
4. This pattern is known as the **Template Method Pattern** тАФ highly relevant in KTU design-pattern questions.

### 3.4 Complete Derivation of Constructor Invocation Order

Let us derive the order of constructor calls in a three-level inheritance chain.

**Code Setup:**

```java
class A {
    A() { System.out.println("A"); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() { System.out.println("B"); }
}
class C extends B {
    C() { System.out.println("C"); }
}
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        C obj = new C();
    }
}
```

**Output Derivation:**

$$
\text{Order of Execution} = \text{TopMostAncestor} \rightarrow \text{Middle} \rightarrow \text{Current}
$$

$$
\text{Execution Order} = A \rightarrow B \rightarrow C
$$

**Output:**
```
A
B
C
```

**Why this order?**

The JVM executes constructors in the order: **parent first, then child**. This guarantees that the inherited members are fully initialized before the sub class constructor body executes any logic that might depend on them.

### 3.5 Analytical Matrix: Member Accessibility Across Super Class Boundary

Let `P` = Public, `R` = Protected, `D` = Default (package-private), `Pr` = Private. The table below shows accessibility in the sub class for each parent access modifier:

$$
\text{Access Matrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
\text{Modifier} & \text{Sub Class (same pkg)} & \text{Sub Class (diff pkg)} & \text{Via Inheritance} \\
P & \text{Yes} & \text{Yes} & \text{Yes} \\
R & \text{Yes} & \text{Yes} & \text{Yes} \\
D & \text{Yes} & \text{No} & \text{No} \\
Pr & \text{No} & \text{No} & \text{No (not directly)}
\end{bmatrix}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner's Note:** Private members ARE inherited (occupy memory in the sub class object), but they are **NOT directly accessible** in the sub class. They can only be accessed via public/protected getter methods. This is a frequently tested distinction.

