## 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

### 4.1 Super Class Inheritance Hierarchy (Mermaid Block Diagram)

```mermaid
graph TD
    objRoot["java lang Object"] --> clsA1["Person Super Class"]
    objRoot --> clsA2["Animal Super Class"]
    clsA1 --> clsB1["Student Sub Class"]
    clsA1 --> clsB2["Faculty Sub Class"]
    clsA2 --> clsC1["Dog Sub Class"]
    clsA2 --> clsC2["Cat Sub Class"]
    clsB1 --> clsD1["GraduateStudent Sub Sub Class"]
    clsB2 --> clsE1["VisitingFaculty Sub Sub Class"]
```

**Interpretation:** Every class in Java implicitly extends `java.lang.Object`. From `Person` (super class), two sub classes (`Student` and `Faculty`) are derived. `Student` is further extended by `GraduateStudent` тАФ forming a **multilevel inheritance chain**.

### 4.2 Memory Layout of a Sub Class Object

```mermaid
graph TD
    memBlock["Sub Class Object in Heap Memory"]
    memBlock --> supPart["Super Class Portion"]
    memBlock --> subPart["Sub Class Portion"]
    supPart --> fld1["Field: name inherited"]
    supPart --> fld2["Field: age inherited"]
    supPart --> mth1["Method: display inherited"]
    subPart --> fld3["Field: rollNo own"]
    subPart --> mth2["Method: study own"]
    mth1 --> supRef["super reference points here"]
```

**Interpretation:** When `new Student()` executes, a single contiguous memory block is allocated. It is partitioned into two logical regions: the super class portion (containing inherited members) and the sub class portion (containing new members). The `super` reference always points to the start of the super class portion.

### 4.3 Constructor Chaining Execution Flow

```mermaid
graph TD
    startNode["main calls new Dog"] --> checkExp["Does Dog constructor have explicit super?"]
    checkExp --> yesPath["Yes super Mammal"]
    checkExp --> noPath["No implicit super inserted by compiler"]
    yesPath --> callA["Animal String constructor executes"]
    noPath --> callA2["Animal no-arg constructor executes"]
    callA --> execB["Dog constructor body executes"]
    callA2 --> execB
    execB --> finishNode["Object fully constructed and returned"]
```

**Interpretation:** Whether explicit or implicit, the super class constructor is always invoked **before** the sub class constructor body. This is enforced by the Java Language Specification (JLS).

### 4.4 Access Modifier Decision Flowchart

```mermaid
graph TD
    qMod["What is the access modifier of the parent member?"]
    qMod --> qPriv["private"]
    qMod --> qDefault["default package private"]
    qMod --> qProt["protected"]
    qMod --> qPub["public"]
    qPriv --> outPriv["NOT accessible directly in sub class use getters"]
    qDefault --> outDefault["Accessible only if sub class is in same package"]
    qProt --> outProt["Accessible in sub class even across packages via inheritance"]
    qPub --> outPub["Always accessible everywhere"]
```

