**Model Solution for Q.A(b) тАФ 7 Marks:**

**Concept (3 marks):** In Java, when an object of a derived class is created, the constructor of the **topmost ancestor** in the inheritance chain is executed first, followed by constructors down the hierarchy until the derived class constructor executes last. This is automatically managed by the compiler through implicit or explicit `super()` calls.

**Code (4 marks):**

```java
class A {
    A() { System.out.println("Constructor A"); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() { System.out.println("Constructor B"); }
}
class C extends B {
    C() { System.out.println("Constructor C"); }
}
public class ChainDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        C obj = new C();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Constructor A
Constructor B
Constructor C
```

**Explanation:** The `new C()` call triggers `C()`'s constructor. The first statement is an implicit `super()` (since not explicitly written), which calls `B()`. `B()`'s implicit `super()` calls `A()`. After `A()` finishes, control returns to `B()`, then to `C()`. Thus the execution order is **A тЖТ B тЖТ C**.

