# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Singleton Pattern тАФ Exhaustive Java Implementation Walkthrough

### 3.1.1 Variation 1: Eager Initialization

```java
public class EagerSingleton {
    // STEP 1: Private static instance тАФ created immediately at class loading
    private static final EagerSingleton instance = new EagerSingleton();

    // STEP 2: Private constructor тАФ prevents external instantiation
    private EagerSingleton() {
        System.out.println("EagerSingleton instance created.");
    }

    // STEP 3: Public static accessor тАФ returns the single instance
    public static EagerSingleton getInstance() {
        return instance;
    }

    public void showMessage() {
        System.out.println("Hello from Eager Singleton!");
    }
}
```

**Logic Walkthrough:**
- The instance is created at the time of class loading (eager).
- It is `final`, so it cannot be reassigned.
- Works in multi-threaded environments because class loading is thread-safe in Java.
- **Drawback:** Instance is created even if `getInstance()` is never called.

---

### 3.1.2 Variation 2: Lazy Initialization (NOT Thread-Safe)

```java
public class LazySingleton {
    // STEP 1: Private static instance тАФ declared but NOT yet created
    private static LazySingleton instance;

    // STEP 2: Private constructor
    private LazySingleton() {
        System.out.println("LazySingleton instance created.");
    }

    // STEP 3: Public static accessor with lazy creation
    public static LazySingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {           // Check first
            instance = new LazySingleton(); // Create only if null
        }
        return instance;                  // Return the (now guaranteed) instance
    }
}
```

**Logic Walkthrough:**
- Instance is created only when `getInstance()` is first called.
- **Race Condition Warning:** If two threads call `getInstance()` simultaneously when `instance == null`, both may create new objects тАФ breaking the Singleton guarantee.
- **Verdict:** Acceptable only in single-threaded contexts.

---

### 3.1.3 Variation 3: Thread-Safe with `synchronized` Method

```java
public class ThreadSafeSingleton {
    private static ThreadSafeSingleton instance;

    private ThreadSafeSingleton() {}

    // The 'synchronized' keyword locks the method for one thread at a time
    public static synchronized ThreadSafeSingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new ThreadSafeSingleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
```

**Logic Walkthrough:**
- The `synchronized` keyword ensures only one thread executes `getInstance()` at a time.
- **Drawback:** Performance overhead тАФ every call acquires the lock, even after the instance is created.

---

### 3.1.4 Variation 4: Double-Checked Locking (with `volatile`)

```java
public class DoubleCheckedSingleton {
    // 'volatile' is CRITICAL here тАФ prevents instruction reordering
    private static volatile DoubleCheckedSingleton instance;

    private DoubleCheckedSingleton() {}

    public static DoubleCheckedSingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {                       // First check (no lock)
            synchronized (DoubleCheckedSingleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {               // Second check (with lock)
                    instance = new DoubleCheckedSingleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
```

**Logic Walkthrough:**

$$
\text{Performance} = \frac{\text{Unlocked fast path (after init)}}{\text{Synchronized only on first call}}
$$

- The first `if` check avoids acquiring the lock on subsequent calls (fast path).
- The second `if` check inside the synchronized block ensures that even if multiple threads passed the first check, only one creates the object.
- The `volatile` keyword guarantees **visibility** across threads and prevents the JVM from reordering the constructor's internal operations.

---

### 3.1.5 Variation 5: Bill Pugh Solution (Recommended Best Practice)

```java
public class BillPughSingleton {
    private BillPughSingleton() {}

    // Static inner class тАФ NOT loaded until getInstance() is called
    private static class SingletonHelper {
        private static final BillPughSingleton INSTANCE = new BillPughSingleton();
    }

    public static BillPughSingleton getInstance() {
        return SingletonHelper.INSTANCE;
    }
}
```

**Logic Walkthrough:**
- The static inner class `SingletonHelper` is **not loaded into memory** until it is referenced.
- When `getInstance()` is called for the first time, the JVM loads `SingletonHelper` and creates the `INSTANCE` тАФ this is thread-safe by JVM guarantee (class loading synchronization).
- No explicit synchronization needed тАФ the simplest and most efficient approach.

---

## 3.2 Adapter Pattern тАФ Exhaustive Java Implementation Walkthrough

### 3.2.1 The Problem Setup
- We have a **Client** that expects a `MediaPlayer` interface (supports `mp3` files).
- We have an **Adaptee** class `AdvancedMediaPlayer` that plays `vlc` and `mp4` files.
- We need an **Adapter** so the Client can play `vlc` and `mp4` via the `MediaPlayer` interface.

### 3.2.2 The Target Interface

```java
// Step 1: Define the Target interface that the Client expects
public interface MediaPlayer {
    void play(String audioType, String fileName);
}
```

### 3.2.3 The Adaptee Classes

```java
// Step 2: Define the Adaptee тАФ advanced media player with different interface
public interface AdvancedMediaPlayer {
    void playVlc(String fileName);
    void playMp4(String fileName);
}

public class VlcPlayer implements AdvancedMediaPlayer {
    @Override
    public void playVlc(String fileName) {
        System.out.println("Playing vlc file. Name: " + fileName);
    }

    @Override
    public void playMp4(String fileName) {
        // Do nothing тАФ VLC player does not support MP4
    }
}

public class Mp4Player implements AdvancedMediaPlayer {
    @Override
    public void playVlc(String fileName) {
        // Do nothing тАФ MP4 player does not support VLC
    }

    @Override
    public void playMp4(String fileName) {
        System.out.println("Playing mp4 file. Name: " + fileName);
    }
}
```

### 3.2.4 The Adapter Class

```java
// Step 3: The Adapter тАФ implements Target, holds Adaptee reference
public class MediaAdapter implements MediaPlayer {

    AdvancedMediaPlayer advancedMusicPlayer;  // Composition (HAS-A)

    public MediaAdapter(String audioType) {
        if (audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("vlc")) {
            advancedMusicPlayer = new VlcPlayer();
        } else if (audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("mp4")) {
            advancedMusicPlayer = new Mp4Player();
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void play(String audioType, String fileName) {
        if (audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("vlc")) {
            advancedMusicPlayer.playVlc(fileName);   // Interface translation
        } else if (audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("mp4")) {
            advancedMusicPlayer.playMp4(fileName);   // Interface translation
        }
    }
}
```

### 3.2.5 The Client (Concrete Implementation of Target)

```java
// Step 4: The Client uses the Target interface (unaware of Adaptee)
public class AudioPlayer implements MediaPlayer {

    MediaAdapter mediaAdapter;

    @Override
    public void play(String audioType, String fileName) {
        // In-built support for mp3
        if (audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("mp3")) {
            System.out.println("Playing mp3 file. Name: " + fileName);
        }
        // Use Adapter for vlc and mp4
        else if (audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("vlc") || audioType.equalsIgnoreCase("mp4")) {
            mediaAdapter = new MediaAdapter(audioType);
            mediaAdapter.play(audioType, fileName);
        }
        else {
            System.out.println("Invalid media. " + audioType + " format not supported.");
        }
    }
}
```

### 3.2.6 The Main Class (Demonstration)

```java
public class AdapterPatternDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        AudioPlayer audioPlayer = new AudioPlayer();

        audioPlayer.play("mp3", "song.mp3");
        audioPlayer.play("mp4", "video.mp4");
        audioPlayer.play("vlc", "movie.vlc");
        audioPlayer.play("avi", "clip.avi");
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
Playing mp3 file. Name: song.mp3
Playing mp4 file. Name: video.mp4
Playing vlc file. Name: movie.vlc
Invalid media. avi format not supported.
```

### 3.2.7 Analytical Matrix тАФ Mapping Calls to Adaptee Methods

| Client Call (`MediaPlayer.play`) | Adapter's Internal Action | Adaptee Method Invoked |
|----------------------------------|---------------------------|------------------------|
| `play("vlc", file)` | Translates `play` тЖТ `playVlc` | `VlcPlayer.playVlc(file)` |
| `play("mp4", file)` | Translates `play` тЖТ `playMp4` | `Mp4Player.playMp4(file)` |
| `play("mp3", file)` | No adapter needed тАФ handled by Client itself | None |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Insight for KTU Exam:** The Adapter does **not** add new functionality. It only **translates** one interface into another. The actual work is still done by the **Adaptee** class. The Adapter is a pure **delegator**.
