| - Singleton()         |  (private constructor)
| + getInstance():      |  (public static)
|     Singleton         |
+-----------------------+
```

**Java Program тАФ Bill Pugh Solution:**

```java
public class BillPughSingleton {
    private BillPughSingleton() {
        System.out.println("Instance created.");
    }

    private static class SingletonHelper {
        // Inner class loaded only when referenced тЖТ lazy + thread-safe
        private static final BillPughSingleton INSTANCE = new BillPughSingleton();
    }

    public static BillPughSingleton getInstance() {
        return SingletonHelper.INSTANCE;
    }

    public void display() {
        System.out.println("Hello from Bill Pugh Singleton!");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BillPughSingleton obj1 = BillPughSingleton.getInstance();
        BillPughSingleton obj2 = BillPughSingleton.getInstance();

        System.out.println("Same instance? " + (obj1 == obj2));
    }
}
```

**Justification тАФ Why Bill Pugh is Best Practice:**
1. **Lazy Initialization:** The static inner class `SingletonHelper` is loaded into memory only when `getInstance()` is referenced for the first time. This avoids the eager-creation drawback.
2. **Thread-Safe Without `synchronized`:** The JVM guarantees that a class is loaded only once, even in concurrent environments, eliminating the need for explicit synchronization.
3. **No Performance Overhead:** Unlike the `synchronized` method approach, there is no lock acquisition on every call тАФ only a single class-load synchronization happens.
4. **Simpler Code:** No `volatile`, no double-checked locking тАФ cleaner and more readable.

