#### Part (b) тАФ 7 Marks
**[KTU University Exam - June 2023, Adapted]**
**Compare and contrast three approaches to implement Singleton in Java: (i) Eager Initialization, (ii) Thread-Safe with `synchronized` method, and (iii) Double-Checked Locking with `volatile`. Provide sample code for each.**

**Model Answer:**

**Comparison Table (7-Mark Detailed Answer):**

| Criterion | Eager Initialization | Synchronized Method | Double-Checked Locking |
|-----------|---------------------|---------------------|------------------------|
| **Instance Creation Time** | At class loading | On first `getInstance()` call | On first `getInstance()` call |
| **Thread-Safe?** | тЬЕ Yes (class loading is thread-safe) | тЬЕ Yes (lock guarantees) | тЬЕ Yes (with `volatile`) |
| **Performance** | тЬЕ Best (no overhead) | тЭМ Worst (lock on every call) | тЬЕ Good (lock only on first call) |
| **Wasted Memory?** | тЭМ Possible (created even if unused) | тЬЕ No | тЬЕ No |
| **Complexity** | тЬЕ Simplest | тЬЕ Simple | тЭМ Complex |
| **Keyword Used** | `final` | `synchronized` | `volatile` + `synchronized` |

**Sample Code тАФ Eager Initialization:**
```java
public class Eager {
    private static final Eager INSTANCE = new Eager();
    private Eager() {}
    public static Eager getInstance() { return INSTANCE; }
}
```

**Sample Code тАФ Thread-Safe Synchronized Method:**
```java
public class SynchSingleton {
    private static SynchSingleton instance;
    private SynchSingleton() {}
    public static synchronized SynchSingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) instance = new SynchSingleton();
        return instance;
    }
}
```

**Sample Code тАФ Double-Checked Locking:**
```java
public class DCLSingleton {
    private static volatile DCLSingleton instance;
    private DCLSingleton() {}
    public static DCLSingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            synchronized (DCLSingleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) instance = new DCLSingleton();
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
```

**Conclusion:** Eager initialization is best when the instance is **always** needed; otherwise, Bill Pugh or Double-Checked Locking are preferred.

