#### Part (b) тАФ 7 Marks
**[KTU University Exam - June 2024, Adapted]**
**Discuss the Object Adapter and Class Adapter variants of the Adapter pattern. Why is Object Adapter preferred in Java? Provide a real-world Java example from the standard library that uses the Adapter pattern.**

**Model Answer:**

**Object Adapter (Composition-based):**
- The Adapter class **holds a reference** to the Adaptee object.
- Uses the **HAS-A** relationship.
- Java supports this natively via instance variables.

**Class Adapter (Inheritance-based):**
- The Adapter class **extends** the Adaptee class and **implements** the Target interface.
- Uses the **IS-A** relationship.
- Requires **multiple inheritance**, which Java does not support for classes.
- Workaround in Java: The Adaptee must be an **interface**, and the Adapter can extend the concrete class while implementing the interface.

**Why Object Adapter is Preferred in Java:**

| Reason | Explanation |
|--------|-------------|
| **No Multiple Inheritance** | Java classes cannot extend more than one class. Object Adapter avoids this issue. |
| **Loose Coupling** | Composition creates weaker coupling than inheritance тАФ easier to change Adaptee later. |
| **Flexibility** | A single Adapter can wrap **multiple Adaptees** if needed (delegating to different objects). |
| **Favor Composition Principle** | The famous GoF principle: **"Favor object composition over class inheritance."** |
| **Runtime Binding** | Adaptee can be swapped at runtime via polymorphism. |

**Real-World Java Standard Library Example:**

> **`java.io.InputStreamReader`** is a textbook Adapter example.
> - It **adapts** an `InputStream` (byte-oriented) into a `Reader` (character-oriented).
> - Client code expects a `Reader` (Target), but reads bytes via `InputStream` (Adaptee).
> - The `InputStreamReader` bridges the two interfaces seamlessly.

**Simplified Illustration:**
```java
InputStream inputStream = new FileInputStream("data.txt");  // Adaptee (bytes)
Reader reader = new InputStreamReader(inputStream);          // Adapter (chars)
// Client can now use reader.read() тАФ character-based interface
```

This is exactly the **Adapter pattern** in action тАФ the underlying stream is byte-based, but the client uses a character-based interface.

