## 3.1 Derivative Case Study: The "OrderProcessor" Anti-Pattern тЖТ SOLID Refactor

### 3.1.1 The Initial Violating Code (Pre-SOLID Baseline)

```java
public class OrderProcessor {
    public void processOrder(String orderId, String customerEmail, double amount,
                              String paymentType, String filePath) {
        // 1. Validation logic
        if (amount <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid amount");
        }
        // 2. Database persistence
        try {
            java.sql.Connection conn = java.sql.DriverManager.getConnection(
                "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/shop", "user", "pass");
            java.sql.PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(
                "INSERT INTO orders (id, email, amount) VALUES (?, ?, ?)");
            ps.setString(1, orderId);
            ps.setString(2, customerEmail);
            ps.setDouble(3, amount);
            ps.executeUpdate();
            conn.close();
        } catch (java.sql.SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        // 3. Payment processing
        if ("CREDIT_CARD".equals(paymentType)) {
            System.out.println("Charging credit card: " + amount);
        } else if ("PAYPAL".equals(paymentType)) {
            System.out.println("Charging PayPal: " + amount);
        } else if ("UPI".equals(paymentType)) {
            System.out.println("Charging UPI: " + amount);
        }
        // 4. File-based receipt generation
        try {
            java.io.FileWriter writer = new java.io.FileWriter(filePath);
            writer.write("Order " + orderId + " confirmed for " + customerEmail);
            writer.close();
        } catch (java.io.IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        // 5. Email notification
        System.out.println("Emailing receipt to " + customerEmail);
    }
}
```

### 3.1.2 Step-by-Step Refactor (SOLID Application)

**Step 1 тАФ Apply SRP: Extract validation, persistence, payment, file I/O, and email into separate classes.**

```java
class OrderValidator {
    public void validate(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid amount");
        }
    }
}
class OrderRepository {
    public void save(String orderId, String email, double amount) {
        try {
            java.sql.Connection conn = java.sql.DriverManager.getConnection(
                "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/shop", "user", "pass");
            java.sql.PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(
                "INSERT INTO orders (id, email, amount) VALUES (?, ?, ?)");
            ps.setString(1, orderId);
            ps.setString(2, email);
            ps.setDouble(3, amount);
            ps.executeUpdate();
            conn.close();
        } catch (java.sql.SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
class ReceiptWriter {
    public void write(String orderId, String email, String filePath) {
        try {
            java.io.FileWriter writer = new java.io.FileWriter(filePath);
            writer.write("Order " + orderId + " confirmed for " + email);
            writer.close();
        } catch (java.io.IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
class EmailNotifier {
    public void sendReceipt(String email) {
        System.out.println("Emailing receipt to " + email);
    }
}
```

**Step 2 тАФ Apply OCP + DIP: Define a `PaymentGateway` abstraction.**

```java
interface PaymentGateway {
    void charge(double amount);
}
class CreditCardGateway implements PaymentGateway {
    public void charge(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Charging credit card: " + amount);
    }
}
class PaypalGateway implements PaymentGateway {
    public void charge(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Charging PayPal: " + amount);
    }
}
class UpiGateway implements PaymentGateway {
    public void charge(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Charging UPI: " + amount);
    }
}
```

**Step 3 тАФ Apply DIP: Refactor `OrderProcessor` to depend on abstractions via constructor injection.**

```java
class OrderProcessor {
    private final OrderValidator validator;
    private final OrderRepository repository;
    private final PaymentGateway paymentGateway;
    private final ReceiptWriter receiptWriter;
    private final EmailNotifier emailNotifier;
    public OrderProcessor(OrderValidator validator, OrderRepository repository,
                          PaymentGateway paymentGateway, ReceiptWriter receiptWriter,
                          EmailNotifier emailNotifier) {
        this.validator = validator;
        this.repository = repository;
        this.paymentGateway = paymentGateway;
        this.receiptWriter = receiptWriter;
        this.emailNotifier = emailNotifier;
    }
    public void processOrder(String orderId, String customerEmail, double amount, String filePath) {
        validator.validate(amount);
        repository.save(orderId, customerEmail, amount);
        paymentGateway.charge(amount);
        receiptWriter.write(orderId, customerEmail, filePath);
        emailNotifier.sendReceipt(customerEmail);
    }
}
```

**Step 4 тАФ Apply ISP: Split `Notifier` if multiple notification channels emerge.**

```java
interface Notifier { void notify(String email); }
interface EmailChannel extends Notifier { }
interface SmsChannel extends Notifier { }
class EmailNotifier implements EmailChannel {
    public void notify(String email) { System.out.println("Emailing " + email); }
}
class SmsNotifier implements SmsChannel {
    public void notify(String phone) { System.out.println("SMS to " + phone); }
}
```

### 3.1.3 LSP Verification тАФ Substitution Test

To prove the refactored design satisfies LSP, we test the polymorphic substitution of `PaymentGateway`:

$$
\forall g \in \{ \text{CreditCardGateway}, \text{PaypalGateway}, \text{UpiGateway} \},
\ \ \text{OrderProcessor.processOrder}(\dots, g, \dots) \text{ produces valid order}
$$

Each subclass:
- Maintains the post-condition: *amount is charged*.
- Does not tighten pre-conditions: *amount > 0* is still required.
- Does not introduce new checked exceptions.

Therefore, the substitution is **behaviorally safe** тАФ LSP holds.

