# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A тАФ Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

### **Q1. [KTU University Exam тАФ Model Question, Module 4]**
**Define the Single Responsibility Principle with a suitable Java example.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)**, the *S* in SOLID, states that **a class should have only one reason to change**, meaning it should have only one well-defined responsibility or job.

**Java Example (2 marks):**

```java
// Violates SRP: Class has multiple responsibilities
class Student {
    void calculateGPA() { /* academic logic */ }
    void saveToDatabase() { /* persistence logic */ }
    void sendEmail() { /* communication logic */ }
}

// SRP-compliant: Separate classes for each responsibility
class StudentGpaCalculator { void calculateGPA(Student s) { } }
class StudentRepository { void save(Student s) { } }
class StudentEmailService { void sendEmail(Student s) { } }
```

The compliant version has **three classes**, each handling **one** responsibility. *(1 mark for definition + 2 marks for example)*

---

### **Q2. [KTU University Exam тАФ Model Question, Module 4]**
**Briefly explain the Liskov Substitution Principle. Why is the classic SquareтАУRectangle example a violation?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

The **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)** states that **objects of a superclass must be replaceable with objects of a subclass without breaking the correctness of the program**. *(1 mark)*

In the classic **Square extends Rectangle** example, LSP is violated because: *(2 marks)*

- `Square.setWidth(w)` also modifies `height` to maintain the square's invariant.
- A client code that does `Rectangle r = new Square(); r.setWidth(5); r.setHeight(10);` expects an area of $50$, but receives $100$.
- The subclass **changes the behavioral contract** (post-conditions) of the setters, breaking the assumption made by the base class.

Hence, `Square` is **not a true behavioral subtype** of `Rectangle`, violating LSP.

