## 5.2 Part B тАФ Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, with Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A (14 Marks) [KTU University Exam тАФ Model Module 4 Question]**

**(a)** Explain all **five SOLID principles** with one Java code snippet for each that demonstrates either compliance or violation. *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Consider a `NotificationService` class in Java that currently sends only email. The class is tightly coupled to the `EmailSender` concrete class. Refactor the code to make it **Dependency-Inversion-Principle compliant** so that it can work with both `EmailSender` and `SmsSender` without modifying the high-level module. Provide the complete refactored code. *(7 marks)*

---

### **Model Solution for Question A:**

#### **Part (a) тАФ All Five SOLID Principles (7 marks)**

*(Award 1.4 marks per principle; distribute marks across definition, code, and explanation)*

**1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) тАФ 1.4 marks**

**Definition**: A class should have one, and only one, reason to change.

**Java Code (Violation & Fix):**

```java
// VIOLATION
class Invoice {
    void calculateTotal() { }
    void printInvoice() { }   // Multiple reasons to change
    void saveToDB() { }
}
// FIX
class Invoice { /* data */ }
class InvoiceCalculator { void calculateTotal(Invoice i) { } }
class InvoicePrinter { void print(Invoice i) { } }
class InvoiceRepository { void save(Invoice i) { } }
```

**2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP) тАФ 1.4 marks**

**Definition**: Open for extension, closed for modification.

```java
abstract class DiscountPolicy {
    abstract double apply(double price);
}
class SeasonalDiscount extends DiscountPolicy {
    double apply(double p) { return p * 0.9; }
}
class LoyaltyDiscount extends DiscountPolicy {
    double apply(double p) { return p * 0.8; }
}
```

Adding a new discount requires only adding a new class, not modifying `DiscountPolicy` or existing ones.

**3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) тАФ 1.4 marks**

**Definition**: Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types.

```java
class Bird { void fly() { System.out.println("Flying"); } }
class Sparrow extends Bird { void fly() { System.out.println("Sparrow flying"); } }
// VIOLATION: Ostrich cannot fly, but extending Bird forces it to.
class Ostrich extends Bird {
    void fly() { throw new UnsupportedOperationException(); } // LSP violation
}
```

**Fix**: Introduce a `FlyingBird` subclass or split the hierarchy.

**4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) тАФ 1.4 marks**

**Definition**: Prefer many small interfaces over one large interface.

```java
interface Printer { void print(); }
interface Scanner { void scan(); }
class AllInOnePrinter implements Printer, Scanner {
    public void print() { }
    public void scan() { }
}
class SimplePrinter implements Printer {
    public void print() { }
}
```

**5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) тАФ 1.4 marks**

**Definition**: High-level modules depend on abstractions, not concretions.

```java
interface DataSource { String read(); }
class Database implements DataSource { public String read() { return "DB data"; } }
class FileSource implements DataSource { public String read() { return "File data"; } }
class ReportService {
    private final DataSource source;
    ReportService(DataSource source) { this.source = source; }
    void generate() { System.out.println(source.read()); }
}
```

#### **Part (b) тАФ DIP Refactor for NotificationService (7 marks)**

**Step 1: Define the abstraction (owned by the high-level module).** *(2 marks)*

```java
// High-level module owns the abstraction
interface MessageSender {
    void send(String recipient, String content);
}
```

**Step 2: Implement the abstraction in low-level modules.** *(2 marks)*

```java
class EmailSender implements MessageSender {
    public void send(String recipient, String content) {
        // SMTP connection logic
        System.out.println("Email sent to " + recipient + ": " + content);
    }
}
class SmsSender implements MessageSender {
    public void send(String recipient, String content) {
        // SMS gateway logic
        System.out.println("SMS sent to " + recipient + ": " + content);
    }
}
```

**Step 3: Refactor `NotificationService` to depend only on the abstraction via constructor injection.** *(2 marks)*

```java
class NotificationService {
    private final MessageSender sender;
    // Constructor injection - DIP compliant
    public NotificationService(MessageSender sender) {
        this.sender = sender;
    }
    public void notifyUser(String recipient, String content) {
        sender.send(recipient, content);
    }
}
```

**Step 4: Demonstrate usage (1 mark):**

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Switch implementations at runtime without modifying NotificationService
        MessageSender email = new EmailSender();
        NotificationService service1 = new NotificationService(email);
        service1.notifyUser("alice@example.com", "Welcome!");

        MessageSender sms = new SmsSender();
        NotificationService service2 = new NotificationService(sms);
        service2.notifyUser("+91-9876543210", "OTP: 123456");
    }
}
```

**Justification (1 mark тАФ to be written in the answer):**
- `NotificationService` now depends on the `MessageSender` **abstraction** rather than a concrete class.
- Adding `PushNotificationSender` requires zero changes to `NotificationService` тАФ this also satisfies **OCP**.
- This design is testable: in unit tests, we can pass a mock `MessageSender` implementation.

