### **Question B (14 Marks) [Alternative Choice тАФ Model Module 4 Question]**

**(a)** Discuss the **Open/Closed Principle (OCP)** and **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)** in detail. For each, provide:
  - A formal definition.
  - A Java code snippet that **violates** the principle.
  - A refactored Java code snippet that **complies** with the principle. *(7 marks)*

**(b)** Design a Java class hierarchy for a **payment processing system** that supports `CreditCard`, `DebitCard`, and `UPIPayment` methods. Apply **all five SOLID principles** in your design. Provide the complete Java code with class diagrams in textual form, and justify each principle's application. *(7 marks)*

---

### **Model Solution for Question B:**

#### **Part (a) тАФ OCP and LSP Detailed (7 marks)**

**Open/Closed Principle (OCP) тАФ 3.5 marks**

**Definition (1 mark)**: A software module should be **open for extension** (new functionality can be added) but **closed for modification** (existing source code is not changed).

**Violating Code (1.25 marks):**

```java
class InvoicePrinter {
    void print(Invoice invoice, String type) {
        if ("PDF".equals(type)) {
            // generate PDF
        } else if ("HTML".equals(type)) {
            // generate HTML
        } else if ("JSON".equals(type)) {
            // generate JSON
        }
    }
}
```

Every time a new format is added, the `print()` method must be **modified**, breaking OCP.

**Compliant Code (1.25 marks):**

```java
interface InvoiceFormatter { String format(Invoice invoice); }
class PdfFormatter implements InvoiceFormatter {
    public String format(Invoice i) { return "PDF " + i.total; }
}
class HtmlFormatter implements InvoiceFormatter {
    public String format(Invoice i) { return "<html>" + i.total; }
}
class JsonFormatter implements InvoiceFormatter {
    public String format(Invoice i) { return "{\"total\":" + i.total + "}"; }
}
class InvoicePrinter {
    private final InvoiceFormatter formatter;
    InvoicePrinter(InvoiceFormatter f) { this.formatter = f; }
    void print(Invoice i) { System.out.println(formatter.format(i)); }
}
```

New formats are added by writing new `InvoiceFormatter` implementations тАФ **no modification** to `InvoicePrinter`.

**Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) тАФ 3.5 marks**

**Definition (1 mark)**: Let $\Phi(x)$ be a property provable about objects $x$ of type $T$. Then $\Phi(y)$ should be true for objects $y$ of type $S$ where $S$ is a subtype of $T$.

**Violating Code (1.25 marks):**

```java
class Vehicle {
    void startEngine() { /* engine starts */ }
}
class Bicycle extends Vehicle {
    void startEngine() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Bicycles have no engine!");
    }
}
```

A `Bicycle` cannot substitute for a `Vehicle` in code that calls `startEngine()`. The pre-condition of the parent (having an engine) is silently broken.

**Compliant Code (1.25 marks):**

```java
abstract class Vehicle { abstract void move(); }
class EngineVehicle extends Vehicle {
    void startEngine() { /* engine starts */ }
    void move() { /* uses engine */ }
}
class Bicycle extends Vehicle {
    void move() { /* pedal power */ }
}
```

Now `Bicycle` is a `Vehicle` that *can move* тАФ a property the base class guarantees тАФ without being forced to expose engine-specific behavior.

#### **Part (b) тАФ Payment System Applying All SOLID Principles (7 marks)**

**Design (Award 1.4 marks per principle):**

```java
// === SRP + DIP: Abstraction owned by the high-level policy module ===
interface PaymentMethod {
    void pay(double amount, String accountId);
}
interface TransactionLogger {
    void log(String transactionId, double amount);
}

// === OCP + LSP: Open for extension; subtypes honor the contract ===
class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentMethod {
    public void pay(double amount, String accountId) {
        System.out.println("Credit card charged: " + amount);
    }
}
class DebitCardPayment implements PaymentMethod {
    public void pay(double amount, String accountId) {
        System.out.println("Debit card charged: " + amount);
    }
}
class UpiPayment implements PaymentMethod {
    public void pay(double amount, String accountId) {
        System.out.println("UPI payment: " + amount + " to " + accountId);
    }
}

// === SRP: A separate class for logging (Single Responsibility) ===
class DatabaseTransactionLogger implements TransactionLogger {
    public void log(String transactionId, double amount) {
        System.out.println("DB log: " + transactionId + " amount " + amount);
    }
}

// === DIP + OCP: High-level module depends on abstractions only ===
class PaymentProcessor {
    private final PaymentMethod method;
    private final TransactionLogger logger;
    public PaymentProcessor(PaymentMethod method, TransactionLogger logger) {
        this.method = method;
        this.logger = logger;
    }
    public void process(String txId, double amount, String accountId) {
        method.pay(amount, accountId);
        logger.log(txId, amount);
    }
}

// === ISP: Each interface is small and focused ===
// (PaymentMethod and TransactionLogger are deliberately small)
```

**Justification (1 mark overall):**

| Principle | Application in Code |
|:---|:---|
| **SRP** | `PaymentProcessor` orchestrates; `PaymentMethod` implementations only charge; `TransactionLogger` only logs. |
| **OCP** | Adding `NetBankingPayment` requires only a new class implementing `PaymentMethod`; no modification to `PaymentProcessor`. |
| **LSP** | Every `PaymentMethod` subclass honors the contract: charging `amount` to `accountId`. No pre-conditions are tightened. |
| **ISP** | Interfaces `PaymentMethod` and `TransactionLogger` are small and role-specific тАФ no fat interface. |
| **DIP** | `PaymentProcessor` depends on abstractions (`PaymentMethod`, `TransactionLogger`), not on `CreditCardPayment` or `DatabaseTransactionLogger` concretely. |

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout тАФ Common Mark Deductions**
> 1. **Memorizing without understanding**: Writing definitions from memory without a *Java code snippet* costs **up to 50% marks** for that sub-question. Always include a code example.
> 2. **Confusing OCP with polymorphism**: OCP is not "use polymorphism" тАФ it is "extend *without modifying* existing tested code." Show this distinction explicitly.
> 3. **LSP misapplication**: Many students write `Square extends Rectangle` as a *compliant* example. It is the **canonical VIOLATION**. Mentioning this earns bonus marks.
> 4. **DIP missing the "inversion"**: A common mistake is using an interface but having the *high-level* module still create the concrete low-level object internally. True DIP requires **injection** (constructor, setter, or framework-based).
> 5. **ISP is not "no interfaces"**: ISP does not forbid interfaces тАФ it forbids *large, unfocused* interfaces. Show segregation explicitly.

