# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 The Swing Class Hierarchy тАФ Structured Logic

The class hierarchy of Swing follows a strict **"ModelтАУViewтАУController (MVC)" design** philosophy, even though the actual implementation uses a slightly modified variant called the **"ModelтАУDelegate"** or **"Separable Model"** architecture.

### Step-by-step logical breakdown:

1. **`java.lang.Object`** тАФ the root of all Java classes.
2. **`java.awt.Component`** тАФ the abstract base for any object that can be displayed on screen and can interact with the user. Defines methods like `setSize()`, `setLocation()`, `repaint()`, `addMouseListener()`.
3. **`java.awt.Container`** тАФ a specialized `Component` that can *hold other components*. Provides `add()`, `remove()`, `setLayout()`.
4. **`javax.swing.JComponent`** тАФ extends `Container`. This is the **base class for almost all Swing components** (except top-level ones). Adds features: tooltips, borders, double-buffering, keyboard mnemonics, pluggable LAF, accessible names.
5. **Concrete Swing components** тАФ e.g., `JButton`, `JLabel`, `JTextField`, `JPanel`, `JSlider`, `JTable`, `JTree`.
6. **Top-level Swing containers** тАФ `JFrame`, `JDialog`, `JApplet` (deprecated). These extend AWT peers because they need a real OS window.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why is `JComponent` so important?** Because it adds the features that distinguish Swing from AWT: tooltips (`setToolTipText()`), borders (`setBorder()`), double-buffering (auto), and most importantly, **pluggable look-and-feel**. Without `JComponent`, Swing would just be AWT in disguise.

## 2.2 The MVC (Model-View-Controller) Architecture in Swing

Although the legacy documentation states that Swing uses MVC, the actual implementation uses a **modified MVC** where the **View and Controller are combined** into a single *UI Delegate* object. The **Model** is separate.

| Component | Role | Example in Swing |
|---|---|---|
| **Model** | Stores the data/state. Knows nothing about display. | `DefaultTableModel`, `ButtonModel`, `ListModel` |
| **View** | Renders the model on screen. | `BasicButtonUI`, `BasicTableUI` (UI Delegates) |
| **Controller** | Handles user input (mouse, keyboard) and updates the model. | UI Delegate + Event Listeners |

> [!NOTE]
> **Why separate Model from View?** It enables powerful features like: a `JTable` can share its `TableModel` with a `JTree`; you can change the look-and-feel at runtime without losing data; and the same data can be rendered differently (e.g., as a table and a chart).

