## 2.4 Layout Managers тАФ The "Floor Plan" Toolkit

Every container has a **Layout Manager** that dictates how its child components are arranged.

| Layout Manager | Arrangement Logic | Common Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| `BorderLayout` | Divides container into **5 regions**: North, South, East, West, Center | Default for `JFrame` content pane |
| `FlowLayout` | Lays out components **left-to-right, top-to-bottom** like text in a paragraph | Default for `JPanel` |
| `GridLayout` | Equal-sized **rows ├Ч columns** grid; each cell same size | Calculator buttons |
| `BoxLayout` | Stacks components in **single row OR single column** with alignments | Toolbars |
| `GridBagLayout` | Most flexible: cells of **varying size, spanning multiple rows/columns** | Complex forms (IDE-style) |
| `CardLayout` | Stacks components like **decks of cards**; show one at a time | Wizards, tab-less navigation |
| `GroupLayout` | Lays out components by **horizontal/vertical groups** (used by NetBeans GUI Builder) | Auto-generated UI code |
| `SpringLayout` | Constraint-based positioning (similar to springs pulling components) | Form designers |

> [!TIP]
> **Default Layouts to Remember (Frequently Asked):**
> - `JFrame`'s content pane тЖТ **BorderLayout**
> - `JPanel` тЖТ **FlowLayout**
> - `JDialog` тЖТ **BorderLayout**

## 2.5 Event Handling тАФ The "Receptionist" Model

Java uses the **Delegation Event Model**: when an event occurs (button click, mouse hover, key press), the source component **delegates** the event to one or more registered **listeners**. Each listener interface defines the methods to be called.

| Listener Interface | Event Class | Key Method(s) |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionListener` | `ActionEvent` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` |
| `MouseListener` | `MouseEvent` | `mouseClicked`, `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited` |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `MouseEvent` | `mouseDragged`, `mouseMoved` |
| `KeyListener` | `KeyEvent` | `keyPressed`, `keyReleased`, `keyTyped` |
| `FocusListener` | `FocusEvent` | `focusGained`, `focusLost` |
| `ItemListener` | `ItemEvent` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e)` |
| `ChangeListener` | `ChangeEvent` | `stateChanged(ChangeEvent e)` |
| `WindowListener` | `WindowEvent` | `windowOpened`, `windowClosing`, `windowClosed`, etc. |
| `ListSelectionListener` | `ListSelectionEvent` | `valueChanged()` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Favorite Question:** "Differentiate between AWT and Swing." Memorize the 8 differences: (1) Package (java.awt vs javax.swing), (2) Weight (heavyweight vs lightweight), (3) Look & Feel (OS-bound vs pluggable), (4) Components (peers vs pure Java), (5) MVC (no vs yes), (6) Thread safety, (7) Double-buffering, (8) Feature richness (no tooltips in AWT, no same-line in `Button`).

## 2.6 Real-World Engineering Utility

Swing is not merely academic тАФ it is widely used in:
- **Banking software** (e.g., older ATMs, banking dashboards)
- **Eclipse IDE** (uses SWT, but concepts are similar; NetBeans uses Swing)
- **NetBeans IDE** (built almost entirely on Swing; 2017 version)
- **IntelliJ IDEA (early versions)** used Swing
- **Apache OpenOffice** suite and many enterprise tools
- **Scientific simulation GUIs** in research labs

In modern industry, Swing has been supplemented by **JavaFX** (now also deprecated in favor of web front-ends), but for KTU 2024 OOP examinations, Swing is the **mandatory** GUI topic.

