# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 The "Anatomy" of a Swing Application тАФ Step-by-Step

Every Swing application, no matter how complex, follows the same **6-step recipe**. Let us derive it step by step.

### Step 1 тАФ Import the required packages

```java
import javax.swing.*;        // Swing components
import java.awt.*;           // AWT base (Color, Font, Layout managers)
import java.awt.event.*;     // Event listener interfaces
```

**Why?** Java needs to know the type names like `JFrame` and `ActionListener` at compile time. Importing avoids fully qualified names.

### Step 2 тАФ Choose the container hierarchy

Decide:
- `JFrame` (main window) тЖТ contains тЖТ `JPanel` (intermediate) тЖТ contains тЖТ components (`JButton`, `JLabel`, `JTextField`).

### Step 3 тАФ Set up the top-level container

```java
JFrame frame = new JFrame("My First Swing App");
frame.setSize(400, 300);
frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
frame.setLayout(new FlowLayout());  // optional; default is BorderLayout
```

### Step 4 тАФ Create and add components

```java
JLabel label = new JLabel("Enter your name:");
JTextField textField = new JTextField(20);
JButton button = new JButton("Submit");

frame.add(label);
frame.add(textField);
frame.add(button);
```

### Step 5 тАФ Register event listeners

```java
button.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String name = textField.getText();
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(frame, "Hello, " + name + "!");
    }
});
```

### Step 6 тАФ Make the frame visible

```java
frame.setVisible(true);
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Critical KTU Pitfall:** `setVisible(true)` must be the **last call** on a frame (or near the end), because once visible, layout negotiations between components have already finished. Adding components *after* `setVisible(true)` requires explicit `revalidate()` and `repaint()` calls.

## 3.2 Worked Example: Full Login Window (Analytical Matrix)

Let us build a **Login Window** that demonstrates 5 concepts simultaneously: (1) Layout, (2) Event handling, (3) Dialog usage, (4) Border, (5) Mnemonics.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class LoginWindow extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    // Step 1: Declare components
    JLabel lblUser, lblPass, lblStatus;
    JTextField txtUser;
    JPasswordField txtPass;
    JButton btnLogin, btnCancel;
    JPanel mainPanel, buttonPanel;

    public LoginWindow() {
        // Step 2: Frame setup
        setTitle("Login - KTU Demo");
        setSize(350, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        // Step 3: Create components
        lblUser   = new JLabel("Username:");
        lblUser.setDisplayedMnemonic('U');  // Alt+U focuses txtUser
        lblPass   = new JLabel("Password:");
        lblPass.setDisplayedMnemonic('P');
        lblStatus = new JLabel(" ");

        txtUser = new JTextField(15);
        txtPass = new JPasswordField(15);

        btnLogin  = new JButton("Login");
        btnLogin.setMnemonic('L');
        btnCancel = new JButton("Cancel");
        btnCancel.setMnemonic('C');

        // Step 4: Register listeners
        btnLogin.addActionListener(this);
        btnCancel.addActionListener(this);

        // Step 5: Build layout
        mainPanel = new JPanel(new GridLayout(2, 2, 5, 5));
        mainPanel.setBorder(BorderFactory.createEmptyBorder(10, 10, 10, 10));
        mainPanel.add(lblUser);
        mainPanel.add(txtUser);
        mainPanel.add(lblPass);
        mainPanel.add(txtPass);

        buttonPanel = new JPanel(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.CENTER, 10, 5));
        buttonPanel.add(btnLogin);
        buttonPanel.add(btnCancel);

        // Step 6: Add to frame
        setLayout(new BorderLayout());
        add(mainPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);
        add(buttonPanel, BorderLayout.SOUTH);
        add(lblStatus, BorderLayout.NORTH);

        // Step 7: Show
        setLocationRelativeTo(null);  // center on screen
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        Object src = e.getSource();
        if (src == btnLogin) {
            String u = txtUser.getText();
            String p = new String(txtPass.getPassword());
            if (u.equals("admin") && p.equals("1234")) {
                lblStatus.setText("Login successful!");
                JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Welcome, " + u + "!");
            } else {
                lblStatus.setText("Invalid credentials.");
                JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Login failed.", 
                    "Error", JOptionPane.ERROR_MESSAGE);
            }
        } else if (src == btnCancel) {
            txtUser.setText("");
            txtPass.setText("");
            lblStatus.setText(" ");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new LoginWindow();
    }
}
```

### Analytical Walkthrough Matrix

| Line / Block | Concept Demonstrated | KTU Exam Relevance |
|---|---|---|
| `extends JFrame implements ActionListener` | Single-class approach to host both UI and event handling | **High** тАФ often asked |
| `new JPasswordField(15)` | Secure field; `getPassword()` returns `char[]` (not `String`) | **High** тАФ security concept |
| `setDisplayedMnemonic('U')` | Keyboard accessibility (Alt+U) | Medium |
| `BorderFactory.createEmptyBorder(...)` | Padding around components without visible border | **High** тАФ frequent API question |
| `setLocationRelativeTo(null)` | Centers window on screen | Low |
| `JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(...)` | Standardized dialog box (4th parameter: message type) | **Very High** |
| `new String(txtPass.getPassword())` | Converting char[] to String for comparison | Medium тАФ common security pitfall |
| `e.getSource()` | Identifying which component fired the event | **High** тАФ event model |

## 3.3 Event Handling Flow тАФ Step-by-Step Derivation

The Delegation Event Model works as follows. Let us trace what happens when a user clicks a `JButton`:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1:} \quad & \text{User clicks the button at coordinates (x, y).} \\
\text{Step 2:} \quad & \text{JVM captures the click via the underlying AWT peer тЖТ creates a new } \texttt{ActionEvent}. \\
\text{Step 3:} \quad & \text{Event is placed on the } \textbf{Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)} \text{ queue.} \\
\text{Step 4:} \quad & \text{EDT picks up the event and calls } \texttt{processEvent()} \text{ on the source component.} \\
\text{Step 5:} \quad & \texttt{processEvent()} \text{ delegates to } \texttt{processActionEvent()}. \\
\text{Step 6:} \quad & \texttt{processActionEvent()} \text{ iterates through the registered } \texttt{ActionListener} \text{s.} \\
\text{Step 7:} \quad & \text{For each listener, the method } \texttt{actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)} \text{ is invoked.} \\
\text{Step 8:} \quad & \text{Listener performs its task (e.g., updates UI, opens dialog, etc.).}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Why is this derivation important?** The model answers the question: *"Where do I put my code when a button is clicked?"* тАФ The answer is **inside `actionPerformed()`** of an `ActionListener` you registered with the button.

## 3.4 Adapter Classes тАФ The Shortcut

Since interfaces like `MouseListener` have **5 abstract methods**, implementing the interface requires stub-implementing all 5 even if you only need one. Java provides **adapter classes** with empty default implementations:

```java
abstract class MouseAdapter implements MouseListener {
    public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {}
    public void mousePressed(MouseEvent e) {}
    public void mouseReleased(MouseEvent e) {}
    public void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e) {}
    public void mouseExited(MouseEvent e) {}
}
```

**Usage:**

```java
myButton.addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
    @Override
    public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {
        // handle only the click
    }
});
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Note:** Adapters exist for: `MouseAdapter`, `MouseMotionAdapter`, `KeyAdapter`, `WindowAdapter`, `FocusAdapter`. Adapters are **abstract**, so you cannot instantiate them directly тАФ you must subclass them or use anonymous classes.

## 3.5 JOptionPane тАФ The "Pre-Built Dialog" Library

`JOptionPane` provides 4 static factory methods for common dialogs:

| Method | Returns | Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| `showMessageDialog(parent, message)` | `void` | Information, warning, error display |
| `showConfirmDialog(parent, message)` | `int` (e.g., `JOptionPane.YES_OPTION`) | Yes/No/Cancel confirmation |
| `showInputDialog(parent, message)` | `String` (or `null` if cancelled) | Simple text input |
| `showOptionDialog(...)` | `int` | Custom button labels & icons |

**Message type icons** (the 3rd parameter in `showMessageDialog`):
- `JOptionPane.PLAIN_MESSAGE` (no icon)
- `JOptionPane.INFORMATION_MESSAGE` (тД╣)
- `JOptionPane.WARNING_MESSAGE` (тЪа)
- `JOptionPane.QUESTION_MESSAGE` (?)
- `JOptionPane.ERROR_MESSAGE` (тЬЦ)

