# ЁЯУШ SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 The Delegation Event Model тАФ The "Why" Behind Swing Events

Before Java 1.1, the **Inheritance Event Model** was used (components inherited and overrode `handleEvent()`). It was inefficient because subclasses had to contain handling code even if not needed. Java 1.1 introduced the **Delegation Event Model**, which **decouples** event generation from event processing.

### 2.1.1 Three-Step Operational Flow

1. **Registration (Subscription Phase):**
   - The listener object is registered with the event source using a method like `addActionListener()`, `addMouseListener()`, etc.
   - Source internally stores the listener in a listener list (often an `EventListener` vector).

2. **Event Generation (Trigger Phase):**
   - User interacts (e.g., clicks a button).
   - Source creates an `EventObject` subclass (e.g., `new ActionEvent(this, ...)`) and invokes the appropriate listener method (`actionPerformed()`).

3. **Event Handling (Response Phase):**
   - The listener's callback method executes.
   - The Event Dispatch Thread (EDT) ensures thread-safety.

---

## 2.2 Event Source Methods: Registration & Removal

Each event category has specific registration methods. Here is the **KTU Cheat Sheet**:

| Event Category | Registration Method | Removal Method | Listener Interface |
|----------------|---------------------|----------------|--------------------|
| **Action** (buttons, menus) | `addActionListener(L)` | `removeActionListener(L)` | `ActionListener` |
| **Mouse** (clicks, moves) | `addMouseListener(L)` | `removeMouseListener(L)` | `MouseListener` |
| **Mouse Motion** (drag, move) | `addMouseMotionListener(L)` | `removeMouseMotionListener(L)` | `MouseMotionListener` |
| **Key** (keyboard) | `addKeyListener(L)` | `removeKeyListener(L)` | `KeyListener` |
| **Window** (open, close) | `addWindowListener(L)` | `removeWindowListener(L)` | `WindowListener` |
| **Focus** | `addFocusListener(L)` | `removeFocusListener(L)` | `FocusListener` |
| **Item** (checkbox, list) | `addItemListener(L)` | `removeItemListener(L)` | `ItemListener` |

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Naming Convention:** KTU examiners love asking "Which method is used to register a mouse listener?" тАФ the answer is always `addMouseListener()`.

---

## 2.3 Detailed Listener Interfaces & Their Abstract Methods

This is the **most high-yield table for KTU exams** тАФ memorize it.

### 2.3.1 `ActionListener` (1 method)

```java
public interface ActionListener extends EventListener {
    void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e);
}
```

### 2.3.2 `MouseListener` (5 methods)

```java
public interface MouseListener extends EventListener {
    void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e);
    void mousePressed(MouseEvent e);
    void mouseReleased(MouseEvent e);
    void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e);
    void mouseExited(MouseEvent e);
}
```

### 2.3.3 `MouseMotionListener` (2 methods)

