## 2.4 Adapter Classes тАФ Solving the "Empty Method" Problem

### 2.4.1 The Problem

If you implement `MouseListener`, Java **forces** you to provide all 5 methods, even if you only care about `mouseClicked()`. This creates boilerplate code.

### 2.4.2 The Solution: Adapters

Java provides **adapter classes** that implement the listener interface with **empty (no-op) methods**. You override only what you need.

| Interface | Adapter Class | Empty Methods Provided |
|-----------|---------------|------------------------|
| `MouseListener` | `MouseAdapter` | 5 |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `MouseMotionAdapter` | 2 |
| `KeyListener` | `KeyAdapter` | 3 |
| `WindowListener` | `WindowAdapter` | 7 |
| `FocusListener` | `FocusAdapter` | 2 |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **No `ActionAdapter` or `ItemAdapter` exist** because their interfaces have only one method, which you would implement directly.

---

## 2.5 Four Ways to Implement Event Handling in Swings

This is a **favorite KTU question** тАФ "List different ways to handle events in Java."

| # | Method | When to Use |
|---|--------|-------------|
| **1** | **Implementing Listener Interface** (separate class) | When listener logic is reused across components. |
| **2** | **Extending Adapter Class** (separate class) | When you need only 1тАУ2 methods of a multi-method interface. |
| **3** | **Anonymous Inner Class** | Quick, one-off handlers (most common in modern Swing). |
| **4** | **Lambda Expression** (Java 8+) | Concise syntax for single-method interfaces (functional interfaces like `ActionListener`). |

---

## 2.6 Key Event Methods (Frequently Tested)

For `MouseEvent` and `KeyEvent`, you must know these **getter methods**:

### MouseEvent Methods
- `int getX()` / `int getY()` тАФ coordinates of mouse.
- `int getClickCount()` тАФ single vs. double-click.
- `int getButton()` тАФ `MouseEvent.BUTTON1`, `BUTTON2`, `BUTTON3`.
- `boolean isShiftDown()`, `isControlDown()`, `isAltDown()` тАФ modifier keys.

### KeyEvent Methods
- `char getKeyChar()` тАФ character typed (only in `keyTyped()`).
- `int getKeyCode()` тАФ virtual key code (e.g., `KeyEvent.VK_ENTER`).
- `String getKeyText(int keyCode)` тАФ human-readable name.
- `boolean isActionKey()` тАФ true for keys without Unicode (F1, arrows).

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Pitfall:** `getKeyChar()` returns `CHAR_UNDEFINED` inside `keyPressed()` and `keyReleased()`. Use `getKeyCode()` instead for non-character keys.

