# ЁЯУШ SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Method 1: Implementing a Listener Interface (Separate Class)

> **Scenario:** A button click should display "Button Clicked!" in a label.

### Step-by-Step Construction

**Step 1:** Import necessary packages.
```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

**Step 2:** Create a class that implements `ActionListener`.
```java
class ButtonHandler implements ActionListener {
    JLabel label;
    ButtonHandler(JLabel label) {
        this.label = label;
    }
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        label.setText("Button Clicked at: " + e.getWhen());
    }
}
```

**Step 3:** Wire it into the main GUI class.
```java
public class Demo1 extends JFrame {
    JLabel label;
    JButton button;
    Demo1() {
        setTitle("Method 1 - Interface Implementation");
        setSize(400, 200);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        label = new JLabel("Press the button");
        button = new JButton("Click Me");

        add(label);
        add(button);

        // REGISTRATION PHASE
        button.addActionListener(new ButtonHandler(label));

        setVisible(true);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Demo1();
    }
}
```

### Analytical Matrix

| Step | What Happens | Memory/Thread Implication |
|------|--------------|---------------------------|
| 1. User clicks button | JVM creates `ActionEvent` object | Created on **EDT** (Event Dispatch Thread). |
| 2. Source invokes listener | `actionPerformed()` is called on EDT | Blocks other GUI updates until it returns. |
| 3. `setText()` updates label | Label repaints | Internal `firePropertyChange()` triggered. |
| 4. Method returns | EDT free for next event | Single-threaded rule preserved. |

---

## 3.2 Method 2: Extending an Adapter Class

> **Scenario:** Close the window when the user clicks the 'X' (close) button.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class Demo2 extends JFrame {
    Demo2() {
        setTitle("Method 2 - Adapter Class");
        setSize(300, 200);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE);
        // We override the default to control closing manually.

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                int choice = JOptionPane.showConfirmDialog(
                    Demo2.this, 
                    "Are you sure you want to exit?", 
                    "Confirm Exit", 
                    JOptionPane.YES_NO_OPTION
                );
                if (choice == JOptionPane.YES_OPTION) {
                    System.exit(0);
                }
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Demo2();
    }
}
```

### Why Adapter? тАФ Exhaustive Reasoning

If we implemented `WindowListener` directly, we would have to write **7 empty methods**. The `WindowAdapter` provides default empty implementations, so we override **only** `windowClosing()`. This is the **Adapter Design Pattern** in action.

---

## 3.3 Method 3: Anonymous Inner Classes

> **Scenario:** Change the background color of the panel when a button is clicked.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class Demo3 extends JFrame {
    Demo3() {
        setTitle("Method 3 - Anonymous Inner Class");
        setSize(400, 200);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        JButton btnRed = new JButton("Red");
        JButton btnBlue = new JButton("Blue");
        JPanel panel = new JPanel();
        panel.add(btnRed);
        panel.add(btnBlue);
        add(panel);

        // Anonymous inner class for Red
        btnRed.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                panel.setBackground(Color.RED);
            }
        });

        // Anonymous inner class for Blue
        btnBlue.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                panel.setBackground(Color.BLUE);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Demo3();
    }
}
```

### Why Anonymous Inner Classes?
- **No new `.java` file** needed.
- **Captures local variables** (like `panel`) effectively тАФ note they must be `final` or "effectively final" in Java 8+.
- **Fast prototyping** for one-off handlers.

---

## 3.4 Method 4: Lambda Expressions (Java 8+)

> **Scenario:** Same as 3.3 but using lambda syntax.

```java
btnRed.addActionListener(e -> panel.setBackground(Color.RED));
btnBlue.addActionListener(e -> panel.setBackground(Color.BLUE));
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Lambdas work because `ActionListener` is a **functional interface** (has exactly one abstract method). They produce `.class` files that are **slightly more efficient** than anonymous classes at runtime.

