# ЁЯУШ SECTION 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Mermaid Diagram: Event Handling Flow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    user[User Action<br/>Click, Type, Move]
    source[Event Source<br/>JButton, JTextField, JFrame]
    edt[Event Dispatch Thread<br/>EDT]
    listener[Event Listener<br/>implements ActionListener etc.]
    handler[Handler Method<br/>actionPerformed, mouseClicked]
    result[GUI Update<br/>setText, setBackground, repaint]

    user -->|interacts with| source
    source -->|creates EventObject| edt
    edt -->|invokes callback| listener
    listener -->|executes| handler
    handler -->|modifies| result
    result -->|repaint event| user
```

**Explanation of the Flow:**

1. The **User** performs a physical action (clicking a mouse, pressing a key).
2. The **Event Source** (the GUI component) detects this and wraps the details into an `EventObject`.
3. The **EDT** picks up the event from the system queue and dispatches it.
4. The **Event Listener** receives the event via its registered callback method.
5. The **Handler Method** executes application logic.
6. The GUI is **updated**, creating a visual feedback loop to the user.

---

## 4.2 Mermaid Diagram: Listener Registration Architecture

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph SourceSide["Event Source (e.g., JButton)"]
        s1[Listener List<br/>Vector of ActionListeners]
    end

    subgraph ListenerSide["Listener Objects"]
        l1[ActionListener 1<br/>actionPerformed]
        l2[ActionListener 2<br/>actionPerformed]
        l3[ActionListener N<br/>actionPerformed]
    end

    reg[addActionListener]
    unreg[removeActionListener]

    reg -->|adds| s1
    unreg -->|removes| s1
    s1 -->|invokes on event| l1
    s1 -->|invokes on event| l2
    s1 -->|invokes on event| l3
```

> [!NOTE]
> A single source can have **multiple listeners** registered. When an event occurs, **all** registered listeners are notified in registration order (for `AWTEventMulticaster`).

