### Model Solution for Q-A(a): 7 Marks

**The four ways to handle events in Java Swing are:**

**1. Implementing a Listener Interface (2 marks):**
Define a separate class that implements the listener interface, then register an instance with the source.

```java
class MyHandler implements ActionListener {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // Handle event
    }
}
button.addActionListener(new MyHandler());
```

**2. Extending an Adapter Class (2 marks):**
Extend an adapter and override only required methods. Useful for multi-method interfaces.

```java
class MyAdapter extends MouseAdapter {
    public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {
        // Only handle click
    }
}
panel.addMouseListener(new MyAdapter());
```

**3. Using Anonymous Inner Classes (2 marks):**
Define and instantiate the listener inline without creating a named class.

```java
button.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // Inline handler
    }
});
```

**4. Using Lambda Expressions (1 mark):** *(Java 8+)*
For functional interfaces like `ActionListener`, lambda syntax provides conciseness.

```java
button.addActionListener(e -> System.out.println("Clicked"));
```

