**Model Solution for (a):**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;

public class ToggleDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    private JLabel statusLabel;
    private JButton toggleButton;
    private boolean isOn = false;

    public ToggleDemo() {
        setTitle("Toggle Demo");
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setSize(250, 100);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        statusLabel = new JLabel("OFF");
        toggleButton = new JButton("Click Me");
        toggleButton.addActionListener(this);

        add(statusLabel);
        add(toggleButton);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        isOn = !isOn;  // Toggle the boolean
        statusLabel.setText(isOn ? "ON" : "OFF");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ToggleDemo();
    }
}
```

**Explanation**:
1. The class `extends JFrame` and `implements ActionListener` so the frame itself acts as the event handler.
2. The boolean `isOn` is toggled using the `!` (NOT) operator on each click.
3. The ternary operator `isOn ? "ON" : "OFF"` updates the label text accordingly.
4. `addActionListener(this)` registers the current frame object as the button's listener.

---

**Model Solution for (b):**

| Aspect | `setSize(int width, int height)` | `pack()` |
|---|---|---|
| **Definition** | Explicitly sets the window dimensions in pixels | Automatically sizes the window to fit its components' preferred sizes |
| **Control** | Full developer control over dimensions | Window size depends on component sizes |
| **Use Case** | When you need a fixed-size window (e.g., splash screen) | When you want the window to dynamically fit contents |
| **Cross-Platform Behavior** | Same pixel size on all systems (may look different on varying DPI) | Adapts gracefully to system font and component sizes |
| **Components Not Yet Added** | Window can be sized even with no components | Requires at least one component to compute size |
| **Method Signature** | `void setSize(int width, int height)` | `void pack()` |
| **Returns** | `void` | `void` |

**Code Example тАФ `setSize()`**:
```java
JFrame f = new JFrame("Fixed Window");
f.setSize(500, 400);  // Forces window to be exactly 500├Ч400 pixels
f.setVisible(true);
```

**Code Example тАФ `pack()`**:
```java
JFrame f = new JFrame("Adaptive Window");
f.add(new JButton("Short"));
f.add(new JButton("A Much Longer Button Label"));
f.add(new JLabel("Some text here"));
f.pack();  // Window auto-sizes to fit all components snugly
f.setVisible(true);
```

**When to Prefer Each**:
- **Prefer `pack()`** for most production Swing applications тАФ it handles platform-specific font metrics and component size variations gracefully.
- **Prefer `setSize()`** when you need a fixed canvas size (e.g., a drawing application, a game window, a splash screen with specific branding dimensions).
- **Can be combined**: Call `pack()` first to auto-size, then call `setSize()` to enforce a minimum width/height if needed.

---

## KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Top 5 Ways Students Lose Marks in JFrame Questions**
> 
> 1. **Forgetting `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)`** тАФ If the program doesn't terminate properly after the window is closed, the examiner deducts 1-2 marks and may ask in viva why the JVM doesn't exit.
> 
> 2. **Wrong import statements** тАФ Writing `import javax.swing.*;` without realizing some questions specifically test knowledge of individual class imports. Both forms are accepted, but mixing them inconsistently looks sloppy.
> 
> 3. **Adding components before setting the layout** тАФ The order matters! Always set the layout first, then add components, then `setSize()`, then `setVisible(true)`. Reverse order can cause rendering glitches.
> 
> 4. **Confusing `Frame` and `JFrame`** тАФ AWT's `Frame` does NOT have `setDefaultCloseOperation()` method (it uses `WindowAdapter` instead). Mixing up the two classes leads to compile-time errors.
> 
> 5. **Missing `main()` method signature** тАФ Writing `public static void Main(String[] args)` (capital M) is a compile error. Java is case-sensitive.

---

## Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **JFrame** is the **top-level container** in Swing, located in `javax.swing` package, extending `java.awt.Frame`.
- It is a **lightweight component** that follows the **MVC architecture** and supports **pluggable Look and Feel**.
- The **four constructors** are: `JFrame()`, `JFrame(String)`, `JFrame(GraphicsConfiguration)`, `JFrame(String, GraphicsConfiguration)`.
- **Essential methods**: `setTitle()`, `setSize()`, `setVisible(true)`, `setDefaultCloseOperation()`, `setLayout()`, `add()`, `pack()`.
- **WindowConstants** (implemented by JFrame) provide four close-operation constants: `DO_NOTHING_ON_CLOSE`, `HIDE_ON_CLOSE`, `DISPOSE_ON_CLOSE`, `EXIT_ON_CLOSE`.
- **JFrame has a layered architecture**: Glass Pane тЖТ Layered Pane тЖТ Content Pane + Menu Bar, all managed by `JRootPane`.
- **Components must be added to the Content Pane** (or use `frame.add()` which auto-delegates to it).
- The **default layout** of the content pane is `BorderLayout`.
- `setVisible(true)` **must be called last** to avoid rendering issues.
- `pack()` is preferred over `setSize()` for adaptive layouts.
- For **event handling**, `JFrame` can implement listener interfaces directly, or you can use separate listener classes.
- The **package name** `javax.swing` (not `java.swing`) тАФ the `x` stands for "extension".
- **Common exam pattern**: Write a program demonstrating JFrame with 2-3 components, layout, and event handling.

