## 2.4 Event Handling: `ActionListener` + `JTextField`

### The `ActionEvent` Lifecycle

$$
\boxed{
\begin{aligned}
\text{1. User types in JTextField} &\rightarrow \text{Document updates internally.} \\
\text{2. User presses ENTER key} &\rightarrow \text{JTextField fires ActionEvent.} \\
\text{3. Event delivered to all registered ActionListeners} &\rightarrow \text{actionPerformed() invoked.} \\
\text{4. Inside actionPerformed()} &\rightarrow \text{getSource() returns the JTextField.} \\
\text{5. Programmer calls getText()} &\rightarrow \text{Reads the current value.}
\end{aligned}
}$$

### Minimal Program Skeleton (High-Yield for KTU 14-Mark Questions)

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class TextFieldDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JTextField tf;
    JLabel lbl;

    public TextFieldDemo() {
        setTitle("JTextField Demo");
        setSize(400, 150);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        lbl = new JLabel("Enter your name:");
        tf  = new JTextField(20);          // 20 columns wide
        tf.addActionListener(this);        // register the listener

        add(lbl);
        add(tf);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String name = tf.getText();
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Hello, " + name + "!");
        tf.setText("");                    // clear the field
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new TextFieldDemo();
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Output behavior:** When the user types `"Anu"` and presses **Enter**, a message dialog pops up showing `"Hello, Anu!"`, and the text field is cleared.

