## 2.5 The `setEchoChar()` Trick тАФ Password Fields

`JTextField` can simulate a **password field** without needing `JPasswordField`:

```java
JTextField password = new JTextField(20);
password.setEchoChar('*');     // text now shows as *****
```

> [!NOTE]
> `JPasswordField` (a subclass of `JTextField`) is essentially a `JTextField` with `setEchoChar()` preset to a bullet character `тАв`. So the *real engineering takeaway* is: **A `JTextField` + `setEchoChar('*')` тЙИ a `JPasswordField`** (functionally similar for simple cases).

---

## 2.6 The `setActionCommand()` Use-Case

When **one listener handles multiple text fields**, `setActionCommand` distinguishes which field triggered the event:

```java
tf1.setActionCommand("USERNAME");
tf2.setActionCommand("PASSWORD");

public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
    String cmd = e.getActionCommand();
    if (cmd.equals("USERNAME")) { /* ... */ }
    else if (cmd.equals("PASSWORD")) { /* ... */ }
}
```

> [!TIP]
> This pattern is **very common** in KTU 14-mark questions involving "Create a login form with username and password fields."

