## 3.2 Complete Program: Calculator with Two `JTextField`s (Step-by-Step)

This is a **typical KTU 14-mark problem**: *"Write a Java Swing program to create a simple calculator using two `JTextField`s for input and four buttons for +, тИТ, ├Ч, ├╖."*

### Step 1: Import the Required Classes
```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
```

> **Why each import?**
> - `javax.swing.*` тЖТ `JFrame`, `JTextField`, `JButton`, `JLabel`, `JOptionPane`
> - `java.awt.*` тЖТ `FlowLayout`, `BorderLayout`, `GridLayout`, `Color`, `Font`
> - `java.awt.event.*` тЖТ `ActionListener`, `ActionEvent`

### Step 2: Class Declaration
```java
public class Calculator extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    // Step 3 goes here
}
```
- We **extend `JFrame`** so the window itself *is* a frame (no need for a separate `JFrame` object).
- We **implement `ActionListener`** so the same class can handle all button clicks.

### Step 3: Declare Components
```java
    JTextField tf1, tf2, tfResult;
    JButton btnAdd, btnSub, btnMul, btnDiv;
    JLabel lblResult;
```
- **3 text fields**: two for inputs, one for the result display.
- **4 buttons**: one for each arithmetic operation.
- **1 label**: optional cosmetic display.

### Step 4: Constructor тАФ Window Setup
```java
    public Calculator() {
        setTitle("Simple Calculator");
        setSize(400, 250);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout(FlowLayout.CENTER, 15, 15));
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        tf1 = new JTextField(10);
        tf2 = new JTextField(10);
        tfResult = new JTextField(15);
        tfResult.setEditable(false);          // read-only output
        tfResult.setBackground(Color.LIGHT_GRAY);

        btnAdd = new JButton("+");
        btnSub = new JButton("-");
        btnMul = new JButton("*");
        btnDiv = new JButton("/");

        // Register this class as listener for all 4 buttons
        btnAdd.addActionListener(this);
        btnSub.addActionListener(this);
        btnMul.addActionListener(this);
        btnDiv.addActionListener(this);

        add(new JLabel("Number 1:"));
        add(tf1);
        add(new JLabel("Number 2:"));
        add(tf2);
        add(btnAdd);
        add(btnSub);
        add(btnMul);
        add(btnDiv);
        add(new JLabel("Result:"));
        add(tfResult);

        setVisible(true);
    }
```

### Step 5: `actionPerformed` тАФ Event Handling
```java
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        try {
            double a = Double.parseDouble(tf1.getText());
            double b = Double.parseDouble(tf2.getText());
            double result = 0;
            char op = ' ';

            if (e.getSource() == btnAdd) { result = a + b; op = '+'; }
            else if (e.getSource() == btnSub) { result = a - b; op = '-'; }
            else if (e.getSource() == btnMul) { result = a * b; op = '*'; }
            else if (e.getSource() == btnDiv) {
                if (b == 0) {
                    JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Cannot divide by zero!");
                    return;
                }
                result = a / b; op = '/';
            }

            tfResult.setText(a + " " + op + " " + b + " = " + result);
        } catch (NumberFormatException ex) {
            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Please enter valid numbers!");
        }
    }
```

> **Step-by-step logic:**
> 1. Read the text from both `tf1` and `tf2`.
> 2. Convert from `String` to `double` using `Double.parseDouble()`.
> 3. Check **which button** was clicked using `e.getSource()`.
> 4. Perform the corresponding arithmetic.
> 5. Display the result in `tfResult` using `setText()`.
> 6. Handle invalid input (non-numeric) using `try-catch` for `NumberFormatException`.
> 7. Handle division by zero explicitly to avoid `ArithmeticException`.

### Step 6: `main` Method
```java
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Calculator();
    }
}
```

