## 3.4 Derivation: Why `setColumns()` Is Preferred Over `setSize()`

**Given:**
- A `JTextField` with `n` columns and font `Font` of size `S` points.

**Derivation of preferred width:**

$$
\boxed{
\begin{aligned}
\text{Average char width} &= 0.5 \times S \;\; (\text{empirical heuristic for proportional fonts}) \\
\text{Preferred width in pixels} &= n \times (0.5 \times S) + \text{insets.left} + \text{insets.right} + 4 \\
\text{Preferred height in pixels} &= S + \text{insets.top} + \text{insets.bottom} + 2
\end{aligned}
}
$$

> **Why this matters:** When you call `setColumns(20)`, the layout manager (e.g., `GridBagLayout`) dynamically computes the pixel size based on the *current font*. If the user changes the system's DPI or font, the field resizes correctly. With `setSize(200, 30)`, the size is **fixed in pixels** and will look wrong on high-DPI screens.

> [!TIP]
> **KTU exam trick:** "Explain why `setColumns()` is preferred over `setSize()` for `JTextField`." тЖТ Answer: **Layout-manager compatibility, DPI independence, font-aware resizing.**

---

## 3.5 The Action Command Default тАФ A Subtle Pitfall

> [!WARNING]
> **Important Subtlety** that KTU may test:

By default, if you do **not** call `setActionCommand()`, then `event.getActionCommand()` returns the **current text** of the `JTextField`, **not** the text at the time the event was fired. This can cause bugs if the text changes between the Enter press and the listener's invocation.

**Best practice:**
```java
tf.setActionCommand("USERNAME_FIELD");   // fixed command string
```

Now `e.getActionCommand()` always returns `"USERNAME_FIELD"`, regardless of the field's current text.

