## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 The Master Skeleton тАФ Reusable for ALL CRUD Operations

Below is the **canonical skeleton** you should memorize. Every CRUD program is just this template with one block changed.

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class StudentDAO {

    // ---------- Step 1: Define Connection Parameters ----------
    static final String URL  = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/ktudb";
    static final String USER = "root";
    static final String PASS = "password";

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // try-with-resources: Auto-closes Connection, Statement, ResultSet
        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS)) {

            // --- The CRUD operation goes here ---

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Why try-with-resources?** Because failing to close a `Connection` causes a **connection pool leak** тАФ a deadly real-world bug. The try-with-resources block guarantees that the `close()` method is called automatically, even if an exception is thrown.

---

### 3.2 CREATE Operation тАФ `INSERT` (Step-by-Step Derivation)

**Goal:** Insert a new student record into the `students` table.

**Assumed Table Schema:**
```sql
CREATE TABLE students (
    id      INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name    VARCHAR(50),
    age     INT,
    course  VARCHAR(40)
);
```

**Step-by-step Code:**

```java
String sql = "INSERT INTO students(name, age, course) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";

try (PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {

    // Step 1: Bind parameters (index starts at 1, not 0!)
    pst.setString(1, "Arjun");
    pst.setInt(2, 21);
    pst.setString(3, "CSE");

    // Step 2: Execute
    int rows = pst.executeUpdate();

    // Step 3: Verify
    System.out.println(rows + " row(s) inserted successfully.");
}
```

**Logical Derivation of Each Step:**

| Step | Code Line | Reason |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | `VALUES (?, ?, ?)` | Placeholders prevent SQL Injection. |
| 2 | `pst.setString(1, ...)` | Index `1` corresponds to the first `?` placeholder. |
| 3 | `executeUpdate()` | DML command тАФ must use this, not `executeQuery()`. |
| 4 | `rows` returned | Confirms how many rows were actually modified. |

---

### 3.3 READ Operation тАФ `SELECT` (Step-by-Step Derivation)

**Goal:** Display all students.

```java
String sql = "SELECT id, name, age, course FROM students";

try (PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql);
     ResultSet rs = pst.executeQuery()) {

    // The cursor 'rs' starts BEFORE the first row.
    while (rs.next()) {
        int id     = rs.getInt("id");
        String nm  = rs.getString("name");
        int age    = rs.getInt("age");
        String cr  = rs.getString("course");

        System.out.println(id + " | " + nm + " | " + age + " | " + cr);
    }
}
```

**Analytical Logic:**

- `rs.next()` does two things: (a) moves the cursor forward by one row, (b) returns `false` when the cursor passes the last row, terminating the `while` loop.
- Column values are retrieved using `getXxx(columnName)` or `getXxx(columnIndex)`.
- The cursor **always starts before the first row** тАФ calling `rs.getInt("id")` without `next()` throws `SQLException`.

---

### 3.4 UPDATE Operation тАФ Step-by-Step Derivation

**Goal:** Change Arjun's course from "CSE" to "IT".

```java
String sql = "UPDATE students SET course = ? WHERE name = ?";

try (PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {
    pst.setString(1, "IT");
    pst.setString(2, "Arjun");

    int rows = pst.executeUpdate();
    if (rows > 0) {
        System.out.println("Update successful.");
    } else {
        System.out.println("No matching record found.");
    }
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mistake:** Forgetting the `WHERE` clause updates **every row** in the table. Always validate that the row count returned is the expected one.

---

### 3.5 DELETE Operation тАФ Step-by-Step Derivation

```java
String sql = "DELETE FROM students WHERE id = ?";

try (PreparedStatement pst = con.prepareStatement(sql)) {
    pst.setInt(1, 101);
    int rows = pst.executeUpdate();
    System.out.println(rows + " row(s) deleted.");
}
```

---

### 3.6 Analytical Matrix тАФ Choosing the Right Method

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Method Selection Logic} &= 
\begin{cases}
\text{executeQuery(sql)} & \text{if SQL starts with SELECT} \\
\text{executeUpdate(sql)} & \text{if SQL starts with INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE} \\
\text{execute(sql)} & \text{if SQL is unknown / multi-result (rare in KTU)}
\end{cases}
\end{aligned}
$$

The boolean return of `execute()` indicates the kind of `ResultSet` produced тАФ KTU questions generally do not test this.

