# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Library Management System (LMS)** is a software application engineered using **Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** principles and **Structured Query Language (SQL)** to automate the cataloging, circulation, and administration of library resources. Under the KTU 2024 Scheme (PBCST304, Module 4), an LMS is treated as a *capstone mini-project* that consolidates **Encapsulation, Inheritance, Polymorphism, and Abstraction** into a single coherent, testable artifact.

The **Circulation Function** тАФ the focal point of this module тАФ is the subsystem that governs the **borrowтАУreturn lifecycle** of a book. Formally, it is a coordinated sequence of operations that:

1. **Validates** the borrowing eligibility of a `User`.
2. **Checks** the availability of a `Book` instance.
3. **Persists** a `BorrowTransaction` record (in-memory object + SQL row).
4. **Mutates** the state of the book (`AVAILABLE тЖТ BORROWED`).
5. **Reverses** these mutations upon a return, computing any fine if applicable.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy тАФ The "Real Library" Mental Model

Imagine walking into your college library at **APJ Abdul Kalam Technological University**.

| Real-World Entity | OOP Counterpart | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| Physical book on a shelf | `Book` object | Holds metadata (title, ISBN, status) |
| Student/Staff ID card | `User` object | Identity + borrowing history |
| Librarian at the desk | `Librarian` object | Privileged actions (add/remove) |
| The whole library building | `Library` object | Aggregates books and users |
| Paper slip stamped on issue | `BorrowTransaction` object | Records the loan event |

When you hand your ID to the librarian, she **does NOT scan your brain** тАФ she consults a **register (database)**. She checks two things: *Are you a registered user?* and *Is the book on the shelf?* If both answers are *yes*, she issues the book and writes a slip. That slip is exactly what a `BorrowTransaction` object represents in code.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Insight for Examiners:** The Circulation function is the *most testable* subsystem of an LMS because every action (borrow, return, renew, reserve) produces an observable state change. This makes it the *preferred viva question* in KTU 2024 Scheme practical examinations.

### 1.3 Standard Metrics & Constants Used in LMS

- **Standard ISBN-13 format:** 13-digit numeric string (e.g., `978-3-16-148410-0`).
- **Default loan period:** **14 days** (configurable per library policy).
- **Fine per overdue day:** **тВ╣2.00** (a typical KTU project default).
- **Maximum books per user:** **3 active loans** (common constraint).
- **Transaction ID format:** `TXN-YYYYMMDD-XXXX` (auto-incremented sequence).

> [!TIP]
> Always declare such policy constants as `public static final` in Java to enforce the **Open/Closed Principle** тАФ the LMS can be reconfigured without modifying business logic.

