# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

## 2.1 The Four OOP Pillars тАФ Mapped to LMS Classes

| OOP Pillar | Definition | LMS Implementation | KTU Weightage |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Encapsulation** | Binding data + methods; hiding internals via access modifiers | `Book.status` is `private`; mutated only via `borrowBook()` / `returnBook()` setters | **High** |
| **Inheritance** | `is-a` relationship; subclass reuses parent structure | `class Librarian extends User` тАФ inherits identity but gains privileged methods | **High** |
| **Polymorphism** | One interface, many implementations | `User.searchBook(...)` overridden in `Librarian` to return privileged metadata | **Medium** |
| **Abstraction** | Hiding complexity behind clean interfaces | `Library` exposes `issueBook(isbn, userId)` тАФ caller never sees the SQL | **High** |

## 2.2 Class-by-Class Responsibility Matrix

| Class | Attributes (State) | Methods (Behaviour) | SQL Mapping |
|---|---|---|---|
| **`Book`** | `title`, `author`, `isbn`, `genre`, `status` (enum) | `markBorrowed()`, `markReturned()`, `toString()` | `BOOKS` table |
| **`User`** | `userId`, `name`, `contact`, `borrowedBooks` (List) | `register()`, `searchBook()`, `getActiveLoanCount()` | `USERS` table |
| **`Librarian`** *(extends User)* | Inherits all + `staffId` | `addBook()`, `removeBook()`, `updateBook()`, `manageUsers()` | Privileged views |
| **`Library`** | `books` (List), `users` (List), `db` (DBConnection) | `issueBook()`, `returnBook()`, `searchBook()`, `searchUser()` | Aggregates all tables |
| **`BorrowTransaction`** | `transactionId`, `book`, `user`, `borrowDate`, `returnDate`, `fine` | `calculateFine()`, `closeTransaction()`, `isOverdue()` | `TRANSACTIONS` table |

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet тАФ Date & Fine Computation

> [!NOTE]
> Since Java's `java.time` API (introduced in Java 8) is the standard, all date arithmetic uses **`LocalDate`**, not the legacy `Date` class.

| Quantity | Formula (Java Equivalent) | Units |
|---|---|---|
| Days borrowed | `ChronoUnit.DAYS.between(borrowDate, returnDate)` | days |
| Overdue days | `max(0, daysBorrowed тИТ loanPeriod)` | days |
| Fine amount | `overdueDays ├Ч finePerDay` | тВ╣ (rupees) |
| Active loan count | `borrowedBooks.stream().filter(b тЖТ b.isActive()).count()` | integer |
| Eligibility check | `(activeLoanCount < MAX_BOOK_LIMIT) && (userStatus == ACTIVE)` | boolean |

### 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet тАФ SQL JOINs Used in Circulation

| Query Purpose | SQL Construct | Example Snippet |
|---|---|---|
| Check book availability | `SELECT status FROM BOOKS WHERE isbn = ?` | Single-row lookup |
| Fetch user's active loans | `SELECT * FROM TRANSACTIONS WHERE user_id = ? AND return_date IS NULL` | Filtered scan |
| Issue a book (atomic) | `BEGIN; UPDATE BOOKS ...; INSERT INTO TRANSACTIONS ...; COMMIT;` | Transaction block |
| Return + fine update | `UPDATE TRANSACTIONS SET return_date = ?, fine = ? WHERE txn_id = ?` | Single update |

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

The LMS pattern appears in production systems as:
- **Public libraries** (Koha, Evergreen тАФ both open-source LMS).
- **University digital repositories** (DSpace, EPrints).
- **E-commerce inventory systems** (Amazon, Flipkart warehouses).
- **Hospital equipment tracking** (asset management with borrow/return semantics).

> [!TIP]
> When you write your KTU project report, cite Koha (used by IIM Bangalore, IIT Delhi) as a **real-world validation** of your design choices. Examiners reward industry awareness.

## 2.6 The Circulation Workflow тАФ Six Logical Phases

1. **Authentication** тАФ Verify `User` exists and is `ACTIVE`.
2. **Eligibility Check** тАФ `activeLoans < MAX_BOOK_LIMIT`.
3. **Availability Check** тАФ `Book.status == AVAILABLE`.
4. **State Mutation** тАФ `Book.status = BORROWED`; `Transaction` created.
5. **Persistence** тАФ `INSERT INTO TRANSACTIONS`; `UPDATE BOOKS SET status='BORROWED'`.
6. **Notification** тАФ Print receipt with `dueDate = borrowDate + 14 days`.
