# 3. Step-by-Step Design Derivations & Implementation Walkthrough

## 3.1 Deriving the Class Hierarchy (Inheritance Tree)

**Step 1 тАФ Identify the *is-a* relationships.**
A `Librarian` **is a** `User` (a librarian is also a registered person with an ID). Therefore, `Librarian` is a subclass of `User`. We do **NOT** make `Librarian` and `User` siblings of a common `Person` class here because the KTU brief explicitly says *"Librarian inherits from User."*

$$
\text{User} \;\xrightarrow{\text{extends}}\; \text{Librarian}
$$

**Step 2 тАФ Identify the *has-a* (composition) relationships.**
- A `Library` *has many* `Book` objects тЖТ aggregation (books can exist independently).
- A `User` *has many* borrowed `Book` references тЖТ composition via list.
- A `BorrowTransaction` *has* exactly one `Book` and one `User` тЖТ strong association.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Library} &\;\circ\!\rightarrow\; \text{Book} \quad (1 \text{ to many}) \\
\text{Library} &\;\circ\!\rightarrow\; \text{User} \quad (1 \text{ to many}) \\
\text{BorrowTransaction} &\;\rightarrow\; \text{Book} \quad (1 \text{ to } 1) \\
\text{BorrowTransaction} &\;\rightarrow\; \text{User} \quad (1 \text{ to } 1)
\end{aligned}
$$

**Step 3 тАФ Identify state, then behaviour.**
For each class, list *data* (attributes) first, then *operations* (methods). This is the KTU-recommended OOA (Object-Oriented Analysis) order.

## 3.2 Deriving the SQL Schema (Logical тЖТ Physical)

Following the normalization rules (1NF, 2NF, 3NF), we derive the following tables:

```sql
-- BOOKS table (normalized to 3NF)
CREATE TABLE BOOKS (
    isbn         VARCHAR(13) PRIMARY KEY,
    title        VARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,
    author       VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    genre        VARCHAR(50),
    status       VARCHAR(20)  NOT NULL DEFAULT 'AVAILABLE',
    CHECK (status IN ('AVAILABLE','BORROWED','RESERVED','LOST'))
);

-- USERS table
CREATE TABLE USERS (
    user_id      VARCHAR(10)  PRIMARY KEY,
    name         VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    contact      VARCHAR(15),
    role         VARCHAR(20)  NOT NULL DEFAULT 'MEMBER',
    CHECK (role IN ('MEMBER','LIBRARIAN'))
);

-- TRANSACTIONS table (associative entity)
CREATE TABLE TRANSACTIONS (
    transaction_id   VARCHAR(20)  PRIMARY KEY,
    isbn             VARCHAR(13)  REFERENCES BOOKS(isbn),
    user_id          VARCHAR(10)  REFERENCES USERS(user_id),
    borrow_date      DATE         NOT NULL,
    due_date         DATE         NOT NULL,
    return_date      DATE,
    fine_amount      DECIMAL(6,2) DEFAULT 0.00
);
```

**Design reasoning for the schema:**
- `isbn` is the natural primary key for `BOOKS` (uniquely identifies an edition).
- `TRANSACTIONS` is a **weak entity** тАФ it depends on `BOOKS` and `USERS`.
- `return_date` is `NULL`-able: `NULL` means the book is still out.
- A `CHECK` constraint enforces the **Book Status** enum at the database layer (defense in depth).

## 3.3 Deriving the `issueBook()` Algorithm (Step-by-Step Pseudocode)

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Algorithm: } & \texttt{issueBook(isbn, userId)} \\
\text{Input: } & \text{book ISBN, user ID} \\
\text{Output: } & \text{Transaction ID or Exception}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Step 1 тАФ Input validation.** Reject empty/null ISBN or userId.
**Step 2 тАФ Load user.** `SELECT * FROM USERS WHERE user_id = ?`. If not found, throw `UserNotFoundException`.
**Step 3 тАФ Eligibility check.** Count active loans:
$$
\text{activeLoans} = \texttt{SELECT COUNT(*) FROM TRANSACTIONS WHERE user\_id = ? AND return\_date IS NULL}
$$
If `activeLoans тЙе MAX_BOOK_LIMIT` (3), throw `LoanLimitExceededException`.
**Step 4 тАФ Book availability check.** `SELECT status FROM BOOKS WHERE isbn = ?`. If `status тЙа 'AVAILABLE'`, throw `BookUnavailableException`.
**Step 5 тАФ Atomic state mutation (begin SQL transaction).**
$$
\begin{aligned}
\texttt{BEGIN TRANSACTION;} \\
\texttt{UPDATE BOOKS SET status = 'BORROWED' WHERE isbn = ?;} \\
\texttt{INSERT INTO TRANSACTIONS (...) VALUES (...);} \\
\texttt{COMMIT;}
\end{aligned}
$$
**Step 6 тАФ In-memory reflection.** Update the `Book` object's `status` field and add the `BorrowTransaction` to the user's `borrowedBooks` list.
**Step 7 тАФ Return the new `Transaction` object** to the caller for receipt generation.

## 3.4 Complete Java Implementation of the Circulation Subsystem

### 3.4.1 The `Book` Class

```java
public class Book {
    private String title;
    private String author;
    private String isbn;
    private String genre;
    private BookStatus status;

    public enum BookStatus { AVAILABLE, BORROWED, RESERVED, LOST }

    public Book(String title, String author, String isbn, String genre) {
        this.title   = title;
        this.author  = author;
        this.isbn    = isbn;
        this.genre   = genre;
        this.status  = BookStatus.AVAILABLE;
    }

    public void markBorrowed() {
        if (this.status != BookStatus.AVAILABLE) {
            throw new IllegalStateException(
                "Book " + isbn + " is not available (current=" + status + ")");
        }
        this.status = BookStatus.BORROWED;
    }

    public void markReturned() {
        this.status = BookStatus.AVAILABLE;
    }

    public BookStatus getStatus() { return status; }
    public String    getIsbn()    { return isbn; }
    public String    getTitle()   { return title; }
    public String    getAuthor()  { return author; }
    public String    getGenre()   { return genre; }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return String.format("[%s] %s by %s (%s) - %s",
                             isbn, title, author, genre, status);
    }
}
```

