# ЁЯУШ MODULE 4 тАФ ONLINE PAYMENT PROCESSING SYSTEM (OOP + DYNAMIC POLYMORPHISM)

## 1.1 Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Formal KTU 2024 Definition:**
> An **Online Payment Processing System** is a software application that accepts, validates, authorises, and records monetary transactions over the internet using multiple payment instruments. In Object-Oriented Programming, such a system is modelled as a hierarchy of cooperating classes where a single super-type reference invokes different sub-type behaviours at run-time тАФ a property called **Dynamic Polymorphism** (also known as *late binding* or *run-time method dispatch*).

### ЁЯОп KTU Syllabus Highlights (Module-4 Mapping)
| OOP Concept | Application in the Project |
|---|---|
| **Abstraction** | Abstract `Payment` class hides the processing logic |
| **Inheritance** | `CreditCardPayment`, `PayPalPayment`, `BankTransferPayment` extend `Payment` |
| **Polymorphism** | `processPayment()` behaves differently for each sub-class |
| **Encapsulation** | Sensitive fields (cardNo, accountNo) are `private` |
| **Dynamic Binding** | JVM resolves overridden methods at run-time, not compile-time |

### ЁЯза Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy тАФ The Bank Teller Window:**
> Imagine you walk up to a bank counter. You simply say *"I want to deposit money"*. The teller (the `PaymentProcessor`) doesn't care *which* payment method you used тАФ cash, cheque, NEFT, UPI, or PayPal. They take your **Payment** (abstract concept) and call the *process* action. Each method has its own internal rules (cash is counted, UPI hits a server, PayPal calls PayPal API), but the **teller uses ONE common instruction** to handle them all. This is exactly what dynamic polymorphism achieves in Java: a single reference type invokes different code depending on the *actual* object stored in memory at run-time.

### ЁЯУМ Key Java Terminology (Bold Constants/Keywords)

- **Abstract Method** тАФ A method declared without an implementation (e.g., `abstract void processPayment();`).
- **Concrete Class** тАФ A class that can be instantiated; provides the *body* for all inherited abstract methods.
- **`@Override` Annotation** тАФ Compiler-time safety check that a method is genuinely overriding a super-type method.
- **Upcasting** тАФ Assigning a sub-class object to a super-class reference (e.g., `Payment p = new CreditCardPayment();`).
- **Dynamic Method Dispatch** тАФ The JVM mechanism that selects the correct overridden method at run-time based on the object's actual class, not the reference's declared type.
- **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)** тАФ Any `Payment` reference *must* be replaceable with `CreditCardPayment`, `PayPalPayment`, or `BankTransferPayment` without breaking program correctness.
