## 1.2 Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### ЁЯФН Theoretical Breakdown тАФ How Dynamic Polymorphism Works in Java

Dynamic polymorphism is the *crown jewel* of the Module-4 inheritance unit. The mechanism can be broken down into **five sequential steps** that the JVM executes every time a polymorphic call is made:

1. **Compile-Time Check (Static Phase)** тАФ The compiler verifies that the method *exists* in the declared reference type. If `Payment` declares `processPayment()`, the compiler permits the call even if the actual object is `CreditCardPayment`. This guarantees **type safety**.
2. **Bytecode Generation** тАФ Java does NOT inline the method call. Instead, the compiler emits an *invokevirtual* bytecode instruction. This instruction does not contain the absolute memory address of the method тАФ it contains a *symbolic reference*.
3. **Class Loading (Linking Phase)** тАФ When the `.class` file is loaded, the JVM builds a **Method Table (vtable)** for each class. The vtable is a static array of method pointers; each entry corresponds to a method declared in the class or inherited from a parent.
4. **Run-Time Resolution (Dynamic Phase)** тАФ When the program actually executes the polymorphic call, the JVM looks at the *real* object on the heap, retrieves its vtable, and jumps to the entry for the method being called. This happens **once per call** unless the JIT (Just-In-Time) compiler inlines it.
5. **Execution** тАФ The selected method body runs. For example, if the object is a `PayPalPayment`, the PayPal-specific authentication logic is executed тАФ even though the reference is of type `Payment`.

> [!TIP]
> **Why "Dynamic"?** Because step-4 happens at *run-time* (dynamically), not at compile-time. If the reference type determined the call, the technique would be called **static polymorphism** (overloading).

### ЁЯУК KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet тАФ Access Modifiers, Keywords & Class Roles

| Element | Keyword / Notation | Role in Project | Default Value / Boundary |
|---|---|---|---|
| `Payment` | `abstract class` | Super-class; **cannot be instantiated** | Methods may be abstract or concrete |
| `processPayment()` | `abstract void` | Force every sub-class to implement | Returns `void`; takes `double amount` |
| `validate()` | `final boolean` | Common logic; **cannot be overridden** | Returns `true` if input is non-null |
| Card Number | `private String` | Encapsulated; accessed via getters | **16 digits**, masked in toString() |
| Payment Methods | `ArrayList<Payment>` | Holds **heterogeneous** Payment objects | Capacity grows dynamically |
| Dynamic call | `payment.processPayment(amt)` | Single call тЖТ many behaviours | Resolved at **run-time** by JVM vtable |
| Compiler hint | `@Override` | Annotation; catches signature typos | Compile-time, not run-time |
| Inheritance | `extends` | Single inheritance in Java | One super-class only |
| `PaymentProcessor` | `public class` | Driver; contains `main(String[])` | Owns the `List<Payment>` |
| Polymorphism rate | `100%` | All `processPayment()` calls are virtual | Static binding ONLY for `static`/`final`/`private` |

### ЁЯПЧя╕П Real-World Engineering Utility

This exact pattern is used in production-level **payment gateways** such as Razorpay, Stripe, and PayPal SDKs. The gateway exposes a *single* `Charge` or `PaymentIntent` interface, but internally maintains concrete classes for Card, UPI, NetBanking, and Wallet. The merchant's code never has to know *which* rail is being used тАФ the JVM dynamically dispatches to the correct processor. This **Open/Closed Principle** (open for extension, closed for modification) is what allows new payment methods like *Apple Pay* or *Crypto* to be added later **without changing existing client code**.

### ЁЯзо Mathematical Cost of Dynamic Dispatch

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Examiners Love This Question:** *"What is the performance cost of dynamic polymorphism?"*

In Big-O terms, dynamic dispatch is **O(1)** тАФ constant time тАФ because the JVM uses a fixed-size vtable indexed by method slot number. However, the constant factor is slightly higher than a direct (static) call due to:
- One extra pointer dereference
- Potential CPU pipeline stalls from indirect branch prediction

Modern **JIT compilers** (HotSpot, OpenJ9) can *devirtualise* hot polymorphic call-sites after enough profiling, recovering the static-call performance. This is why **micro-benchmarks** often show no measurable difference.
