### тЪая╕П KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common ways KTU students LOSE marks on this topic:**
> 1. **Forgetting `@Override` annotation** тАФ KTU examiners explicitly award **0.5 marks** for `@Override` in overriding methods. Omitting it signals carelessness.
> 2. **Making `processPayment()` `static` or `private`** тАФ this **kills** dynamic polymorphism. Static methods are *not* overridden (they are hidden); private methods are *not* inherited. Always keep polymorphic methods `public` and non-static.
> 3. **Forgetting to call `super()` in sub-class constructor** тАФ Java implicitly inserts `super()` only if you write no constructor at all. If you write a constructor and forget `super(...)`, **compile-time error**.
> 4. **Trying `new Payment(...)` in `main()`** тАФ `Payment` is abstract; this throws `Cannot instantiate abstract class` error. Many students do this mistakenly.
> 5. **Not demonstrating the polymorphic call in the driver** тАФ just defining sub-classes is not enough. You MUST show the line `p.processPayment(...)` where `p` is of type `Payment` and the loop iterates over a *mixed* `List<Payment>`.
> 6. **Forgetting `equals()`/`hashCode()` for `ArrayList.contains()`** тАФ not strictly required for this project, but a common follow-up question in Part A.
> 7. **Using `instanceof` checks in the loop** тАФ this **defeats the purpose** of polymorphism. The whole point is to NOT know the type at compile-time. If you write `if (p instanceof CreditCardPayment)`, you lose 2 marks immediately.

